1
00:00:58,536 --> 00:01:01,471
[BellsChiming ]

2
00:01:16,754 --> 00:01:19,689
[ Zither ]

3
00:02:44,275 --> 00:02:46,800
[ Man Narrating ]
I never knew the old Vienna
before the war...

4
00:02:46,878 --> 00:02:49,039
with its Strauss music,
its glamor and easy charm.

5
00:02:49,113 --> 00:02:51,775
Constantinople
suited me better.

6
00:02:51,849 --> 00:02:56,286
I really got to know it in
the classic period of the black market.

7
00:02:56,354 --> 00:02:59,323
We'd run anything if people wanted it
enough and had the money to pay.

8
00:02:59,390 --> 00:03:02,325
Of course, a situation like that
does tempt amateurs...

9
00:03:02,393 --> 00:03:05,453
but, you know, they can't stay
the course like a professional.

10
00:03:05,530 --> 00:03:08,761
Now the city, it's divided
into four zones, you know,

11
00:03:08,833 --> 00:03:12,564
each occupied by a power-- the American,
the British, the Russian and the French.

12
00:03:12,637 --> 00:03:15,105
But the center of the city,
that's international,

13
00:03:15,173 --> 00:03:18,108
policed by an international patrol,
one member of each of the four powers.

14
00:03:18,176 --> 00:03:21,771
Wonderful! What a hope they had,
all strangers to the place...

15
00:03:21,846 --> 00:03:24,144
and none of them
could speak the same language,

16
00:03:24,215 --> 00:03:26,809
except a sort of smattering
of German.

17
00:03:26,884 --> 00:03:30,115
Good fellows, on the whole.
Did their best, you know.

18
00:03:30,188 --> 00:03:33,954
Vienna doesn't really look any worse
than a lot of other European cities.
Bombed about a bit.

19
00:03:34,025 --> 00:03:37,153
Oh, wait. I was gonna tell you
about Holly Martins,

20
00:03:37,228 --> 00:03:40,322
an American, came all the way
here to visit a friend of his.

21
00:03:40,398 --> 00:03:42,593
The name was Lime.
Harry Lime.

22
00:03:42,667 --> 00:03:45,795
Now, Martins was broke, and Lime
had offered him some sort of a job.

23
00:03:45,870 --> 00:03:50,136
Anyway, there he was, poor chap,
happy as a lark and without a cent.

24
00:04:01,519 --> 00:04:03,612
- Passport, please.
- Oh.

25
00:04:03,688 --> 00:04:06,816
- What's the purpose of your visit here?
- A friend offered me a job.

26
00:04:06,891 --> 00:04:09,655
- Where are you staying?
- With him. 15 Stiffgasse.

27
00:04:09,727 --> 00:04:11,888
- His name?
- Lime. Harry Lime.

28
00:04:11,963 --> 00:04:14,955
- Okay.
- Thought he'd be here to meet me.

29
00:04:34,118 --> 00:04:37,053
[ Man Singing In German ]

30
00:04:41,659 --> 00:04:43,593
[ Bell Rings ]

31
00:04:45,229 --> 00:04:49,757
[ Man Speaking German ]

32
00:04:52,270 --> 00:04:54,534
- Speak English?
- English?

33
00:04:54,605 --> 00:05:00,066
[ Mutters ]
A little, little.

34
00:05:00,144 --> 00:05:03,170
[ Speaking German ]

35
00:05:03,247 --> 00:05:05,715
Ten minutes too late.

36
00:05:05,783 --> 00:05:08,081
- Already gone.
- Who?

37
00:05:08,152 --> 00:05:11,781
Mmm, his friends
and, uh, no--

38
00:05:11,856 --> 00:05:14,825
- Uh, coffin.
- Coffin?

39
00:05:14,892 --> 00:05:17,019
Mr. Lime's.
An accident.

40
00:05:17,095 --> 00:05:20,929
Knocked over by a car,
here in front of the house.

41
00:05:20,998 --> 00:05:25,298
Have seen it myself.
Killed at once, immediately.

42
00:05:25,369 --> 00:05:29,897
Already in hell...
or in heaven.

43
00:05:29,974 --> 00:05:35,071
Sorry for the gravediggers.
Hard work. It is frost.

44
00:05:46,257 --> 00:05:49,954
Can you tell me, uh,
who's the--

45
00:05:50,027 --> 00:05:52,257
A fellow called Lime.

46
00:06:01,372 --> 00:06:03,636
[ Speaking German ]

47
00:06:12,717 --> 00:06:15,948
[ Speaking German ]

48
00:06:16,020 --> 00:06:20,423
[ Priest Continues In German ]

49
00:06:25,830 --> 00:06:28,822
[ Mourners Repeating Priest ]

50
00:07:03,901 --> 00:07:06,699
[ German ]

51
00:07:20,084 --> 00:07:24,521
Like a lift to town?
I've got a car here.

52
00:07:30,728 --> 00:07:32,662
Thanks.

53
00:07:40,905 --> 00:07:43,772
- My name's Calloway.
- Martins.

54
00:07:43,841 --> 00:07:46,833
- You a friend of Lime?
- Y eah.

55
00:07:46,911 --> 00:07:50,347
- Been here long?
- No.

56
00:07:59,357 --> 00:08:02,520
You've had a bit of a shock, haven't
you? You could do with a drink.

57
00:08:02,593 --> 00:08:05,494
- Could you buy me one?
- Of course.

58
00:08:05,563 --> 00:08:07,622
- Thanks.
- Schmolka?

59
00:08:07,698 --> 00:08:12,397
I guess nobody knew Harry
like he did, or like I did.

60
00:08:12,470 --> 00:08:16,634
- How long ago?
- Back in school.

61
00:08:16,707 --> 00:08:20,143
I was never so lonesome
in my life till he showed up.

62
00:08:20,211 --> 00:08:22,736
- When did you see him last?
- September, '39.

63
00:08:22,813 --> 00:08:24,872
- When the business started?
- Mm-hmm.

64
00:08:24,949 --> 00:08:27,110
- See much of him before that?
- Once in a while.

65
00:08:27,184 --> 00:08:30,950
- Best friend I ever had.
- That sounds like a cheap novelette.

66
00:08:32,990 --> 00:08:36,323
[ Groans ]
Well, I write cheap novelettes.

67
00:08:36,394 --> 00:08:39,488
I'm afraid I've never heard of you.
What's your name again?

68
00:08:39,563 --> 00:08:41,963
- Holly Martins.
- No, sorry.

69
00:08:42,033 --> 00:08:45,161
You ever hear of
The Lone Rider of Santa Fe?

70
00:08:45,236 --> 00:08:47,329
Can't say that I have.

71
00:08:47,405 --> 00:08:50,772
Death at Double-X Ranch?
Uh, ""raunch.""

72
00:08:50,841 --> 00:08:53,810
- Nope.
- [ Groans ]

73
00:08:53,878 --> 00:08:57,746
He must've known I was broke.
He even sent me an airplane ticket.

74
00:08:57,815 --> 00:09:00,613
- It's a shame.
- What?

75
00:09:00,685 --> 00:09:03,677
Him dying like that.

76
00:09:03,754 --> 00:09:06,348
Best thing that
ever happened to him.

77
00:09:06,424 --> 00:09:08,517
What are you trying to say?

78
00:09:08,592 --> 00:09:11,254
He was about the worst
racketeer in this city.

79
00:09:11,329 --> 00:09:14,594
- Policeman, huh?
- Come on, have another drink.

80
00:09:14,665 --> 00:09:18,192
No, I never did like policemen.
I have to call them sheriffs.

81
00:09:18,269 --> 00:09:21,170
- Ever seen one?
- Pin it on a dead man.

82
00:09:21,238 --> 00:09:25,538
Some petty racket
with gasoline or something.

83
00:09:25,609 --> 00:09:29,636
Just like a cop.
You're a real cop, I suppose.

84
00:09:29,714 --> 00:09:32,842
- It wasn't petrol.
- So it wasn't petrol.

85
00:09:32,917 --> 00:09:35,784
So it was tires
or saccharin or--

86
00:09:35,853 --> 00:09:39,016
Why don't you catch
a few murderers for a change?

87
00:09:39,090 --> 00:09:42,389
Well, you could say that murder
was part of his racket.

88
00:09:44,295 --> 00:09:48,231
It's all right, Paine. He's only
a scribbler with too much drink in him.

89
00:09:48,299 --> 00:09:50,824
Take Mr. Holly Martins home.

90
00:09:50,901 --> 00:09:54,837
Holly Martins, sir?
The, uh, the writer?

91
00:09:54,905 --> 00:09:57,339
The author of
Death at Double-X Ranch?

92
00:09:57,408 --> 00:09:59,968
- [ Martins ] Listen, Callaghan--
- Calloway. I'm English.

93
00:10:00,044 --> 00:10:02,979
You're not going to close your
files at a dead man's expense.

94
00:10:03,047 --> 00:10:06,813
So you're going to find me
the real criminal? Sounds
like one of your stories.

95
00:10:06,884 --> 00:10:09,478
When I'm finished with you,
you'll leave Vienna.

96
00:10:09,553 --> 00:10:12,488
Here's some army money. It should see
you through tonight at Sacher's Hotel,

97
00:10:12,556 --> 00:10:14,922
if you don't drink too much
in the bar.

98
00:10:14,992 --> 00:10:17,756
We'll keep a seat for you
on tomorrow's plane.

99
00:10:21,832 --> 00:10:25,529
Please be careful, sir.
Up we come.

100
00:10:25,603 --> 00:10:28,595
- Written anything lately?
- [ Calloway ] Take him to Sacher's.

101
00:10:28,672 --> 00:10:31,072
Don't hit him again
if he behaves.

102
00:10:31,142 --> 00:10:33,940
And you go carefully there.
It's a military hotel.

103
00:10:34,011 --> 00:10:38,345
I'm so glad to have met you, sir.
I've read quite a few of your books.

104
00:10:38,416 --> 00:10:41,180
- Auf Wiedersehen.
- I like a good western.

105
00:10:41,252 --> 00:10:44,744
That's what I like about them. You can
pick them up and put them down anytime.

106
00:10:44,822 --> 00:10:46,756
- Oh, Mr. Hartman?
- Y es, sir?

107
00:10:46,824 --> 00:10:49,349
Mr. Calloway said this gentleman's
got to have a room for the night.

108
00:10:49,427 --> 00:10:51,361
Passport, please.

109
00:10:51,429 --> 00:10:54,728
Can't very well
introduce you to everybody.

110
00:10:54,799 --> 00:10:57,632
Would you mind
filling this in?

111
00:10:57,701 --> 00:10:59,692
- Mr. Crabbin.
- What is it, sergeant?

112
00:10:59,770 --> 00:11:01,897
- Mr. Holly Martins, the author.
- Who?

113
00:11:01,972 --> 00:11:04,372
- Thought you might be interested.
- Never heard of him.

114
00:11:04,442 --> 00:11:07,377
He's very good, sir.
I've read quite a few of his books.

115
00:11:07,445 --> 00:11:10,710
Author? Martins?
Thank you, sergeant.

116
00:11:10,781 --> 00:11:13,875
Mr. Martins?
My name's Crabbin.

117
00:11:13,951 --> 00:11:16,613
I represent
the C.R.S. of G.H.Q.

118
00:11:16,687 --> 00:11:19,781
- You do?
- Yes. Cultural Reeducation Section.

119
00:11:19,857 --> 00:11:22,382
Propaganda. Very important
in a place like this.

120
00:11:22,460 --> 00:11:25,395
We do a little show each week.
Last week we had ""Hamlet.""

121
00:11:25,463 --> 00:11:28,193
The week before
we had... something.

122
00:11:28,265 --> 00:11:31,200
- The striptease, sir.
- Y es, the Hindu dancers. Thank you.

123
00:11:31,268 --> 00:11:34,237
This is the first opportunity
of making an American author welcome.

124
00:11:34,305 --> 00:11:36,603
- Welcome?
- I'll tell you what, Mr. Martins.

125
00:11:36,674 --> 00:11:40,542
On Wednesday night,
we're having a little lecture
on the contemporary novel.

126
00:11:40,611 --> 00:11:43,580
- Thought perhaps you'd like to speak.
- They wouldn't know me.

127
00:11:43,647 --> 00:11:46,582
Nonsense. Your novels are very
popular here. Aren't they, sergeant?

128
00:11:46,650 --> 00:11:49,414
- Very popular.
- Are you staying long?

129
00:11:49,487 --> 00:11:52,422
How long can one stay here
on this stage money?

130
00:11:52,490 --> 00:11:55,323
Listen, Mr. Martins,
if you'd agree to be our guest,

131
00:11:55,392 --> 00:11:58,088
- we'd be delighted to have you.
- [ Phone Rings ]

132
00:11:58,162 --> 00:12:00,494
- Would you?
- As long as you care to stay.

133
00:12:00,564 --> 00:12:04,000
- He's due to leave tomorrow.
- Have you got a toothache.

134
00:12:04,068 --> 00:12:06,969
- Number 8, Mr. Martins.
- Come upstairs a moment.

135
00:12:07,037 --> 00:12:10,097
- I know a very good dentist.
- I don't need a dentist.
Somebody hit me, that's all.

136
00:12:10,174 --> 00:12:13,166
Goodness. We must report that.
Were they trying to rob you?

137
00:12:13,244 --> 00:12:16,179
Oh, just a soldier. I was trying
to punch his major in the eye.

138
00:12:16,247 --> 00:12:19,011
- A major? Were you really?
- Heard of Harry Lime?

139
00:12:19,083 --> 00:12:21,244
I've heard of him,
but I didn't exactly know him.

140
00:12:21,318 --> 00:12:24,754
- I was going to stay with him,
but he died Thursday.
- Goodness, that's awkward.

141
00:12:24,822 --> 00:12:28,349
Is that what you say to people after
death? ""Goodness, that's awkward""?

142
00:12:28,425 --> 00:12:31,861
- Mr. Martins? Excuse me. Telephone.
- Who is it?

143
00:12:31,929 --> 00:12:36,127
- Baron Kurtz.
- Must be some mistake. Y es?

144
00:12:36,200 --> 00:12:38,725
[ Man On Phone ]
I was a friend of Harry Lime.

145
00:12:38,802 --> 00:12:41,965
I'd very much like to meet you, Baron.
Come around.

146
00:12:42,039 --> 00:12:44,530
Austrians aren't allowed
in your hotel.

147
00:12:44,608 --> 00:12:47,270
- Couldn't we meet at the Mozart Cafe?
- Where?

148
00:12:47,344 --> 00:12:50,279
- Just around the corner.
- How will I know you?

149
00:12:50,347 --> 00:12:54,545
I'll carry a copy of one of your books.
Harry gave it to me.

150
00:12:54,618 --> 00:12:57,246
Be there in a moment.
Wait a minute.

151
00:12:57,321 --> 00:12:59,983
If I do this lecture business,
you'll put me up here a while?

152
00:13:00,057 --> 00:13:01,991
- Certainly.
- It's a deal.

153
00:13:02,059 --> 00:13:05,153
- Did you ever read
The Lone Rider of Santa Fe?
- No, not that one.

154
00:13:05,229 --> 00:13:08,528
It's a story about a man
who hunted down a sheriff who
was victimizing his best friend.

155
00:13:08,599 --> 00:13:10,624
- Seems exciting.
- It is.

156
00:13:10,701 --> 00:13:13,898
I'm gunning just the same way
for your Major Callaghan.

157
00:13:13,971 --> 00:13:15,996
Sounds anti-British, sir.

158
00:13:29,787 --> 00:13:32,187
- Baron Kurtz?
- Mr. Martins?

159
00:13:32,256 --> 00:13:35,714
Delighted to meet you.
Come, let's sit down here.

160
00:13:35,793 --> 00:13:37,761
[ Speaking German ]

161
00:13:37,828 --> 00:13:40,558
- What would you like? Tea? Coffee?
- Coffee.

162
00:13:40,631 --> 00:13:43,065
[ Speaking German ]

163
00:13:43,133 --> 00:13:45,693
It's wonderful how
you keep the tension.

164
00:13:45,769 --> 00:13:47,396
- Tension?
- Suspense.

165
00:13:47,471 --> 00:13:51,908
- You really liked it?
- At the end of every chapter
you are left guessing.

166
00:13:51,976 --> 00:13:54,240
So, you were
a friend of Harry's?

167
00:13:54,311 --> 00:13:57,576
I think his best.
Except you, of course.

168
00:13:57,648 --> 00:14:02,483
The police have a crazy notion that he
was mixed up in some sort of a racket.

169
00:14:02,553 --> 00:14:07,923
Everyone in Vienna is. We all sell
cigarettes and that kind of thing.

170
00:14:07,992 --> 00:14:12,929
I tell you, I've done things that would
have seemed unthinkable before the war.

171
00:14:12,997 --> 00:14:17,934
Once when I was hard up,
I sold some tires on the black market.

172
00:14:18,002 --> 00:14:20,835
I wonder what my father
would have said.

173
00:14:20,904 --> 00:14:23,668
I'm afraid the police
meant more than that.

174
00:14:23,741 --> 00:14:26,403
They get rather absurd
ideas sometimes.

175
00:14:26,477 --> 00:14:29,275
He's somewhere now
he won't mind about that.

176
00:14:29,346 --> 00:14:33,783
Even so, I'm not going to leave
it at this. Would you help me?

177
00:14:35,719 --> 00:14:40,520
I wish I could. But,
you know, I am an Austrian.

178
00:14:40,591 --> 00:14:43,651
I have to be
careful with the police.

179
00:14:43,727 --> 00:14:46,753
I'm afraid
I can't help you.

180
00:14:46,830 --> 00:14:50,197
Except with advice,
of course.

181
00:14:50,267 --> 00:14:52,201
Advice.

182
00:14:53,504 --> 00:14:55,995
We came out of his place
like this...

183
00:14:56,073 --> 00:14:58,701
and were walking this way.

184
00:14:58,776 --> 00:15:01,939
A friend of his called to him
from over there.

185
00:15:02,012 --> 00:15:06,676
Harry went across, and
from up there came the truck.

186
00:15:06,750 --> 00:15:09,742
It was just about here.

187
00:15:11,221 --> 00:15:14,850
- Here?
- Yes.

188
00:15:14,925 --> 00:15:17,553
His friend and l
picked him up,

189
00:15:17,628 --> 00:15:21,086
carried him across over here.

190
00:15:21,165 --> 00:15:26,228
- [ Car Horn Honks ]
- It was a terrible thing. Terrible.

191
00:15:26,303 --> 00:15:29,704
We laid him down
just about here.

192
00:15:31,975 --> 00:15:33,909
And this is where he died.

193
00:15:33,977 --> 00:15:36,138
Even at the end,
his thoughts were of you.

194
00:15:36,213 --> 00:15:38,647
What did he say?

195
00:15:38,716 --> 00:15:41,480
I can't remember
the exact words, Holly.

196
00:15:41,552 --> 00:15:45,352
I may call you Holly, mayn't l?
He always called you that to us.

197
00:15:45,422 --> 00:15:48,414
He was anxious I should
look after you when you arrived,

198
00:15:48,492 --> 00:15:52,155
to see that you got safely home,
tickets, you know, and all that.

199
00:15:52,229 --> 00:15:55,164
But he said he died
instantaneously.

200
00:15:58,068 --> 00:16:00,593
Well, he died before
the ambulance could reach us.

201
00:16:00,671 --> 00:16:05,472
Well, there was only you and
this friend of his. Uh, who was he?

202
00:16:05,542 --> 00:16:07,874
A Romanian. Mr. Popescu.

203
00:16:07,945 --> 00:16:11,108
- I'd like to talk to him.
- H-He has left Vienna.

204
00:16:14,451 --> 00:16:16,385
[ Dog Whimpering ]

205
00:16:16,453 --> 00:16:18,683
- Uh, excuse me.
- Yes?

206
00:16:18,756 --> 00:16:22,852
- Did you know Mr. Lime well?
- Mr. Lime? Yes.

207
00:16:22,926 --> 00:16:25,759
- You remember me. U-Upstairs.
- Yes, I remember you.

208
00:16:25,829 --> 00:16:28,127
Who used to visit Mr. Lime?

209
00:16:28,198 --> 00:16:30,291
Visit? Eh--

210
00:16:30,367 --> 00:16:33,666
[ Speaking German ]

211
00:16:41,311 --> 00:16:44,576
- What did he say?
- He says he doesn't know everybody.

212
00:16:44,648 --> 00:16:47,139
[ Woman Speaking German ]

213
00:16:47,217 --> 00:16:49,879
[ German ]

214
00:16:52,322 --> 00:16:54,290
Excuse me.

215
00:16:57,327 --> 00:16:59,261
Who was at the funeral
besides you?

216
00:16:59,329 --> 00:17:01,991
Only his doctor, Dr. Winkel.

217
00:17:02,065 --> 00:17:04,431
Wasn't there a girl there?

218
00:17:04,501 --> 00:17:08,699
Some girl of the Josefstadt Theater.
You know what Harry was.

219
00:17:08,772 --> 00:17:11,764
You oughtn't to speak to her.
It would only cause her pain.

220
00:17:11,842 --> 00:17:15,938
Not necessarily.
She'd probably want to help.

221
00:17:16,013 --> 00:17:18,743
What's the good
of another postmortem?

222
00:17:18,816 --> 00:17:22,582
Suppose you dig up something
discreditable to Harry?

223
00:17:22,653 --> 00:17:25,918
- Would you give me your address?
- I live in the Russian sector.

224
00:17:25,989 --> 00:17:28,651
But you'll find me at
the Casanova Club every night.

225
00:17:28,725 --> 00:17:31,250
One has to work the best way
one can, you know.

226
00:17:31,328 --> 00:17:33,762
- What's the name of this girl?
- I don't know.

227
00:17:33,831 --> 00:17:35,924
I don't think I ever heard it.

228
00:17:35,999 --> 00:17:38,934
You did mention the theater.

229
00:17:39,002 --> 00:17:41,163
Josefstadt.

230
00:17:41,238 --> 00:17:44,696
But I still think
it won't do Harry any good.

231
00:17:44,775 --> 00:17:47,608
You'd do better
to think of yourself.

232
00:17:47,678 --> 00:17:50,476
[ Chuckles ]
I'll be all right.

233
00:17:50,547 --> 00:17:54,176
Of course.
I'm so glad I've met you.

234
00:17:54,251 --> 00:17:58,585
A master of suspense!
Such a good cover, I think.

235
00:18:01,525 --> 00:18:04,289
- Number 8, please.
- Mr. Calloway's compliments.

236
00:18:04,361 --> 00:18:07,626
- Here's the ticket
for the plane tomorrow.
- Tell the major I won't need it.

237
00:18:07,698 --> 00:18:11,065
Oh, porter, order me a ticket tonight
for the Josefstadt Theater.

238
00:18:11,134 --> 00:18:13,295
- Ah, Mr. Martins!
- Good evening, Mr. Crabbin.

239
00:18:13,370 --> 00:18:16,464
He said I was to drive you
to the airfield or the bus,
whichever you prefer.

240
00:18:16,540 --> 00:18:20,408
Didn't you hear Mr. Crabbin offer me
the hospitality of the H.Q.B.M.T.?

241
00:18:20,477 --> 00:18:23,412
[ Speaking German ]

242
00:19:13,363 --> 00:19:16,491
I was a friend of Harry Lime.

243
00:19:18,302 --> 00:19:21,738
- [ Laughter, Chattering ]
- Afterwards.

244
00:19:21,805 --> 00:19:24,501
[ Speaking German ]

245
00:19:26,143 --> 00:19:29,306
[ Audience Laughing ]

246
00:19:41,792 --> 00:19:43,726
Uh, Miss Schmidt?

247
00:19:43,794 --> 00:19:46,126
Oh, come in.

248
00:19:46,196 --> 00:19:48,221
- Thank you.
- Sit down.

249
00:19:48,298 --> 00:19:51,893
- I enjoyed the play very much.
- Danke. Guten Nacht.

250
00:19:51,969 --> 00:19:54,904
- Guten Nacht.
- You were-- You were awfully good.

251
00:19:54,972 --> 00:19:59,568
- Do you understand German?
- No, l-- Excuse me.
I could follow it fine.

252
00:19:59,643 --> 00:20:03,579
- Oh, yes.
- Perhaps Harry told you about me.
My name is Holly Martins.

253
00:20:03,647 --> 00:20:06,411
- No, he never told me about his friends.
- Oh.

254
00:20:06,483 --> 00:20:09,577
- Would you like some tea?
Someone threw me this packet last week.
- Thank you.

255
00:20:09,653 --> 00:20:13,145
Sometimes the British do instead of
flowers, you know, on the first night.

256
00:20:13,223 --> 00:20:16,249
That was a bouquet from an American.
Would you rather have whiskey?

257
00:20:16,326 --> 00:20:19,659
- Oh, tea's fine.
- Good. I wanted to sell it.

258
00:20:19,730 --> 00:20:24,030
- Oh, there is some tea left.
- Had you known him some time?

259
00:20:26,103 --> 00:20:29,368
- Yes.
- I wanted to talk to you--
No, thank you.

260
00:20:29,439 --> 00:20:31,737
I wanted to talk to you about him.

261
00:20:31,808 --> 00:20:35,266
There's nothing really to talk about,
is there? Nothing.

262
00:20:35,345 --> 00:20:38,405
Well, I saw you
at the funeral.

263
00:20:38,482 --> 00:20:41,610
I'm so sorry.
I didn't notice much.

264
00:20:43,587 --> 00:20:46,317
You were in love with him,
weren't you?

265
00:20:46,390 --> 00:20:50,952
I don't know. How can you know
a thing like that afterwards?

266
00:20:51,028 --> 00:20:55,158
I don't know anything anymore,
except I want to be dead too.

267
00:20:55,232 --> 00:20:57,393
Some more tea?

268
00:20:57,467 --> 00:21:01,494
No, no tea.
Would you like a cigarette?

269
00:21:01,571 --> 00:21:04,131
Oh, American.
Thank you. I like them.

270
00:21:04,207 --> 00:21:08,576
I was talking to another friend
of Harry's, a Baron Kurtz.

271
00:21:08,645 --> 00:21:10,704
- Do you know him?
- No.

272
00:21:10,781 --> 00:21:13,978
- He's got a little dog.
- Oh, yes, yes.

273
00:21:14,051 --> 00:21:16,747
Don't understand what Harry saw
in a fellow like that.

274
00:21:16,820 --> 00:21:20,017
That was the man who brought me
some money when Harry died.

275
00:21:20,090 --> 00:21:22,854
He said Harry had been
anxious at the last moment.

276
00:21:22,926 --> 00:21:25,861
Hmm. He said
he remembered me too.

277
00:21:25,929 --> 00:21:28,955
Seems to show
he wasn't in much pain.

278
00:21:29,032 --> 00:21:31,296
Dr. Winkel told me that.

279
00:21:31,368 --> 00:21:34,030
Dr. Winkel?
Who's he?

280
00:21:34,104 --> 00:21:38,803
A doctor Harry used to go to.
He was passing just after it happened.

281
00:21:38,875 --> 00:21:41,241
- His own doctor?
- Y es.

282
00:21:41,311 --> 00:21:44,678
Well, were you
at the inquest?

283
00:21:44,748 --> 00:21:47,683
Y es. They said it wasn't
the driver's fault.

284
00:21:47,751 --> 00:21:50,686
Harry had often said what
a careful driver he was.

285
00:21:50,754 --> 00:21:53,689
- He was Harry's driver?
- Mm-hmm.

286
00:21:53,757 --> 00:21:58,091
Well, uh,
I don't get it.

287
00:21:58,161 --> 00:22:02,689
All of them there!
Uh, Kurtz, this Romanian, uh, Popescu,

288
00:22:02,766 --> 00:22:05,030
his own driver
knocking him over,

289
00:22:05,102 --> 00:22:07,627
his own doctor
just passing by.

290
00:22:07,704 --> 00:22:10,172
No strangers there at all.

291
00:22:10,240 --> 00:22:12,834
I know. I've wondered
about it a hundred times,

292
00:22:12,909 --> 00:22:15,400
if it really was an accident.

293
00:22:20,117 --> 00:22:22,483
What difference does it make?
He's dead, isn't he?

294
00:22:22,552 --> 00:22:24,543
- But if it wasn't an--
- [ Woman ] Frau Schmidt!

295
00:22:24,621 --> 00:22:28,022
[ Speaking German ]

296
00:22:28,091 --> 00:22:31,060
I must hurry. They don't like
us to use the lights.

297
00:22:31,128 --> 00:22:34,495
- The porter saw it happen.
- Then why worry?

298
00:22:37,834 --> 00:22:40,064
Look, do you know
that porter?

299
00:22:41,972 --> 00:22:43,405
Y es.

300
00:22:44,474 --> 00:22:47,409
[ Speaking German ]

301
00:22:49,479 --> 00:22:52,073
- What's he saying?
- He says it happened right down there.

302
00:22:52,149 --> 00:22:54,913
Happened, yes.
Happened right down there.

303
00:22:54,985 --> 00:22:58,079
- You saw it?
- Well, not saw, heard.

304
00:22:58,155 --> 00:23:01,454
Heard. I heard the brakes.
[ Makes Screeching Sound ]

305
00:23:01,525 --> 00:23:05,017
And I got to the window and saw them
carry the body to the other side...

306
00:23:05,095 --> 00:23:09,031
uh, Josef, the Josef--

307
00:23:09,099 --> 00:23:11,590
Emperor Josef statue.

308
00:23:11,668 --> 00:23:14,603
Why didn't they
bring him in the house?

309
00:23:38,562 --> 00:23:41,326
- Could he have been conscious?
- Conscious?

310
00:23:41,398 --> 00:23:45,801
- [ German ]
- Uh, was he-- was he still alive?

311
00:23:45,869 --> 00:23:49,066
Ah, alive!
He couldn't have been alive,

312
00:23:49,139 --> 00:23:52,472
not with his head
in the way it was.

313
00:23:52,542 --> 00:23:55,067
I was told that
he did not die at once.

314
00:23:55,145 --> 00:23:57,136
[ Speaking German ]

315
00:23:57,214 --> 00:23:59,148
No, I mean that--

316
00:23:59,216 --> 00:24:01,150
[ German ]

317
00:24:01,218 --> 00:24:03,379
No, you--

318
00:24:07,457 --> 00:24:10,756
- He was quite dead.
- He was-- He was quite dead.

319
00:24:10,827 --> 00:24:13,261
He was quite dead.

320
00:24:13,330 --> 00:24:15,764
[ Holly ]
But this sounds crazy.

321
00:24:15,832 --> 00:24:19,666
If he was killed at once,
how could he have talked about
me and this lady here?

322
00:24:19,736 --> 00:24:22,603
Why didn't you say all this
at the inquest?

323
00:24:22,672 --> 00:24:26,699
Uh, it's better not to be
mixed up in things like this.

324
00:24:26,776 --> 00:24:29,176
Things like what?

325
00:24:29,246 --> 00:24:33,546
I was not the only one
who did not give evidence.

326
00:24:33,617 --> 00:24:35,050
Who else?

327
00:24:35,118 --> 00:24:38,417
Three men helped to carry
your friend to the statue.

328
00:24:38,488 --> 00:24:40,012
- Kurtz?
- Y es.

329
00:24:40,090 --> 00:24:41,955
- The Romanian?
- Y es.

330
00:24:42,025 --> 00:24:45,256
- And?
- There was a third man.
He didn't give evidence.

331
00:24:45,328 --> 00:24:47,262
- You mean the doctor?
- No, no, no.

332
00:24:47,330 --> 00:24:50,595
He came later, after they
carried him to the Josef statue.

333
00:24:50,667 --> 00:24:53,192
What did this man look like?

334
00:24:53,270 --> 00:24:55,397
I didn't see his face.

335
00:24:58,441 --> 00:25:04,107
He didn't look up.
He was quite, uh, ordinary.

336
00:25:04,180 --> 00:25:08,480
He-- He might have been...

337
00:25:08,551 --> 00:25:10,485
just anybody.

338
00:25:12,289 --> 00:25:14,223
Just anybody.

339
00:25:14,291 --> 00:25:17,021
[ Phone Ringing ]

340
00:25:17,093 --> 00:25:19,891
Hello? Hello.

341
00:25:19,963 --> 00:25:22,090
[ Speaking German ]

342
00:25:22,165 --> 00:25:24,099
Hello.

343
00:25:25,435 --> 00:25:27,699
[ German ]

344
00:25:29,172 --> 00:25:30,730
Hello?

345
00:25:32,909 --> 00:25:36,242
- Who was that?
- I don't know. They didn't answer.

346
00:25:36,313 --> 00:25:38,804
But I was told
there were only two men there.

347
00:25:38,882 --> 00:25:41,248
You've got to tell
your story to the police.

348
00:25:41,318 --> 00:25:44,776
The police? Why police?
[ Speaking German ]

349
00:25:44,854 --> 00:25:48,051
It's nonsense! It is all nonsense!
It was an accident

350
00:25:48,124 --> 00:25:50,354
You don't know
it was an accident.

351
00:25:50,427 --> 00:25:53,362
- You only saw a dead man
with three men carrying him.
- [ German ]

352
00:25:53,430 --> 00:25:55,762
I should have listened
to my wife.

353
00:25:55,832 --> 00:25:58,426
She said you were
up to no good. Gossip.

354
00:25:58,501 --> 00:26:00,435
[ Holly ] Suppose I take
your evidence to the police?

355
00:26:00,503 --> 00:26:02,767
[ Man Shouting In German ]

356
00:26:02,839 --> 00:26:05,000
[ Holly ]
Now, hold on.

357
00:26:05,075 --> 00:26:08,044
[ Shouting Continues ]

358
00:26:10,347 --> 00:26:13,612
I have no evidence.
I- I saw nothing, I said nothing.

359
00:26:13,683 --> 00:26:15,878
- It's not my business.
- We'll make it your business.

360
00:26:15,952 --> 00:26:18,648
[ Man Shouting In German ]

361
00:26:18,722 --> 00:26:21,691
[ Holly ]
Hold on.

362
00:26:21,758 --> 00:26:25,285
[ Shouting Continues ]

363
00:26:25,362 --> 00:26:29,230
I have always liked you, but you
must not bring this gentleman again.

364
00:26:29,299 --> 00:26:32,063
You must go at once,
please. Please!

365
00:26:32,135 --> 00:26:35,571
[ Speaking German ]
Please!

366
00:26:35,638 --> 00:26:38,368
[ Man Continues Shouting In German ]

367
00:26:39,909 --> 00:26:41,843
[ Streetcar Bell Rings ]

368
00:26:41,911 --> 00:26:44,812
You shouldn't get
mixed up in this.

369
00:26:44,881 --> 00:26:49,011
Well, if I do find out something,
can I look you up again?

370
00:26:49,085 --> 00:26:51,417
Why don't you leave
this town? Go home.

371
00:26:51,488 --> 00:26:54,252
[ Speaking German ]

372
00:27:01,331 --> 00:27:03,925
- What is it?
- [ Continues In German ]

373
00:27:04,000 --> 00:27:05,934
[ German ]

374
00:27:11,274 --> 00:27:14,937
- What's she talking about?
- The police are searching my room.

375
00:27:15,011 --> 00:27:18,105
[ Continues Speaking German ]

376
00:27:45,508 --> 00:27:48,477
- What the devil?
- Getting around, Martins?

377
00:27:48,545 --> 00:27:51,207
Oh, pinning things
on girls now.

378
00:27:51,281 --> 00:27:54,409
Miss Schmidt, I should like
to see your papers, please.

379
00:27:54,484 --> 00:27:57,282
Don't you give him anything.

380
00:27:57,353 --> 00:27:59,287
Thank you.

381
00:28:01,191 --> 00:28:04,251
You were born in Graz
of Austrian parents?

382
00:28:04,327 --> 00:28:06,352
Y es.

383
00:28:06,429 --> 00:28:08,363
Paine.

384
00:28:16,606 --> 00:28:18,540
Hmm.

385
00:28:23,980 --> 00:28:27,143
It's very good, sir,
isn't it, eh?

386
00:28:27,217 --> 00:28:29,412
How much did you pay
for this?

387
00:28:31,020 --> 00:28:33,682
I'm afraid I shall have to keep
this for a while, Miss Schmidt.

388
00:28:33,756 --> 00:28:36,987
- How do you expect her
to live without her papers?
- Write her out a receipt.

389
00:28:37,060 --> 00:28:40,291
- Give her a receipt
for those letters too.
- This way, miss.

390
00:28:40,363 --> 00:28:43,423
I suppose it wouldn't interest you
to know that Harry Lime was murdered.

391
00:28:43,500 --> 00:28:47,095
You're too busy. You haven't even
bothered to get the complete evidence.

392
00:28:54,043 --> 00:28:57,535
- Must you take those?
- They'll be returned, miss.

393
00:28:57,614 --> 00:29:00,378
They are private letters.

394
00:29:00,450 --> 00:29:02,543
That's all right, miss.
Don't worry.

395
00:29:02,619 --> 00:29:05,554
We're used to it.
Like doctors.

396
00:29:05,622 --> 00:29:09,558
There was a third man there. I suppose
that doesn't sound peculiar to you.

397
00:29:09,626 --> 00:29:14,256
I'm not interested in whether
a racketeer like Lime was killed
by his friends or by accident.

398
00:29:14,330 --> 00:29:16,355
The only important thing
is that he's dead.

399
00:29:18,134 --> 00:29:21,365
- I'm sorry.
- Tactful too, aren't we, Callaghan?

400
00:29:21,437 --> 00:29:23,632
- Calloway.
- Must you take those letters?

401
00:29:23,706 --> 00:29:26,197
- Yes, I'm afraid so.
- They're Harry's.

402
00:29:26,276 --> 00:29:30,269
- That's the reason.
- You won't learn anything from them.

403
00:29:30,346 --> 00:29:34,146
They're only... Iove letters.
There are not many of them.

404
00:29:34,217 --> 00:29:37,653
They'll be returned to you,
Miss Schmidt, as soon as
they've been examined.

405
00:29:37,720 --> 00:29:41,656
There's nothing in them.
Harry never did anything.

406
00:29:41,724 --> 00:29:44,488
Only a small thing once,
out of kindness.

407
00:29:44,561 --> 00:29:48,759
- And what was that?
- You've got it in your hand.

408
00:29:48,831 --> 00:29:51,265
[ Sergeant ]
Major Calloway?

409
00:29:51,334 --> 00:29:54,269
- Finished?
- Y es. Okay.

410
00:29:54,337 --> 00:29:57,829
You will have to come
with us, Miss Schmidt.

411
00:29:57,907 --> 00:30:01,741
- You're not locking her up.
- Go home, Martins, like a sensible chap.

412
00:30:01,811 --> 00:30:04,837
- Get the next plane.
- As soon as I get to the bottom of this.

413
00:30:04,914 --> 00:30:07,974
Death's at the bottom
of everything, Martins.

414
00:30:08,051 --> 00:30:12,283
Mind if I use that line in my
next western? You can't chuck me out.

415
00:30:12,355 --> 00:30:16,291
- Here we are, miss.
Your receipt for the letters.
- I don't want it.

416
00:30:16,359 --> 00:30:19,294
Well, I've got it
when you want it, miss.

417
00:30:22,865 --> 00:30:25,834
Anything really wrong
with your papers?

418
00:30:28,504 --> 00:30:31,098
They're forged.

419
00:30:31,174 --> 00:30:33,574
Oh.

420
00:30:33,643 --> 00:30:35,668
Why?

421
00:30:35,745 --> 00:30:39,374
The Russians would claim me.
I come from Czechoslovakia.

422
00:30:39,449 --> 00:30:42,111
[ Speaking German ]

423
00:31:02,805 --> 00:31:06,764
- What'd she say?
- Only complaining about the way
they behaved in her house.

424
00:31:06,843 --> 00:31:10,745
[ Continues Speaking German ]

425
00:31:10,813 --> 00:31:14,146
Give her some cigarettes.

426
00:31:15,685 --> 00:31:18,620
- Uh, cigarettes, hmm?
- Danke.

427
00:31:18,688 --> 00:31:21,088
No, go ahead, take the--

428
00:31:23,159 --> 00:31:26,094
Miss Schmidt, ready?

429
00:31:26,162 --> 00:31:28,562
Now, look,

430
00:31:28,631 --> 00:31:33,227
I'll straighten out
all this nonsense about Harry.

431
00:31:34,637 --> 00:31:36,571
You'll be all right.

432
00:31:38,875 --> 00:31:41,503
Sometimes he said
I laughed too much.

433
00:31:44,647 --> 00:31:47,582
Oh, what's the name of that doctor?
Harry's doctor?

434
00:31:47,650 --> 00:31:51,609
- Dr. Winkel.
- What do you want to see a doctor for?

435
00:31:51,688 --> 00:31:54,486
- A bruised lip.
- Good.

436
00:31:54,557 --> 00:31:58,084
[ Woman Continues
Complaining In German ]

437
00:32:08,638 --> 00:32:12,005
Laboratory, we're coming right down.

438
00:32:18,548 --> 00:32:20,675
You wait here, Miss Schmidt.

439
00:32:44,440 --> 00:32:47,273
[ Train Whistle Blows ]

440
00:32:47,343 --> 00:32:50,676
- [ Man Speaking German ]
- [ Doorbell Buzzes ]

441
00:32:54,050 --> 00:32:56,917
- Is Dr. Winkel in?
- [ Speaking German ]

442
00:32:56,986 --> 00:32:59,978
- Dr. Winkel. I'm sorry.
I don't speak German.
- Nein.

443
00:33:00,056 --> 00:33:04,390
Please, won't you say that
I'm a friend of Harry Lime?

444
00:33:04,460 --> 00:33:07,554
[ Speaking German ]

445
00:33:07,630 --> 00:33:09,689
- Bitte.
- Thank you.

446
00:33:11,134 --> 00:33:14,331
- Bittesehr.
- [ Clock Chiming ]

447
00:33:23,679 --> 00:33:26,170
Guten Nacht.

448
00:33:26,249 --> 00:33:29,412
- Dr. Winkel?
- ""Vinkel.""

449
00:33:29,485 --> 00:33:31,646
Uh, Dr. ""Vinkel.""

450
00:33:31,721 --> 00:33:35,282
Quite a collection
of, uh... collection.

451
00:33:35,358 --> 00:33:37,656
- Y es.
- [ Dog Barking ]

452
00:33:37,727 --> 00:33:41,493
- [ Dog Whimpering ]
- [ Winkel Speaking German ]

453
00:33:48,638 --> 00:33:50,970
Is that your dog?

454
00:33:51,040 --> 00:33:53,065
Y es. Would you mind, Mr., uh--

455
00:33:53,142 --> 00:33:55,372
- Martins.
- Martins, coming to the point, please?

456
00:33:55,444 --> 00:33:57,571
- Thank you.
- I have guests waiting.

457
00:33:57,647 --> 00:34:01,242
- We were both friends of Harry Lime.
- I was his medical advisor.

458
00:34:01,317 --> 00:34:04,343
- I want to find out all I can.
- Find out?

459
00:34:04,420 --> 00:34:07,412
- Y eah, the details.
- I can tell you very little.

460
00:34:07,490 --> 00:34:11,586
He was run over by a car.
He was dead when I arrived.

461
00:34:11,661 --> 00:34:15,461
- Who was with him?
- Two friends of his.

462
00:34:15,531 --> 00:34:18,159
You sure? Two?

463
00:34:18,234 --> 00:34:21,169
Quite sure.

464
00:34:21,237 --> 00:34:23,501
Could he have been
at all conscious?

465
00:34:23,573 --> 00:34:27,475
I understand he was, yes,
for a short time...

466
00:34:27,543 --> 00:34:29,977
while they carried him
across the road.

467
00:34:30,046 --> 00:34:33,038
- In great pain?
- Mmm, not necessarily.

468
00:34:33,115 --> 00:34:36,243
Could he have been capable
of making plans...

469
00:34:36,319 --> 00:34:40,779
for me and others just,
just during those few moments?

470
00:34:40,857 --> 00:34:43,792
I understand he left some
instructions before he died.

471
00:34:43,860 --> 00:34:47,125
I cannot give an opinion.
I was not there.

472
00:34:47,196 --> 00:34:51,565
My opinion is limited
to the causes of death.

473
00:34:53,836 --> 00:34:56,327
Have you any reason
to be dissatisfied?

474
00:34:56,405 --> 00:34:59,340
Was it possible
that his death...

475
00:34:59,408 --> 00:35:02,502
might have been
not accidental?

476
00:35:04,247 --> 00:35:06,545
Could he have been--

477
00:35:06,616 --> 00:35:10,746
Could he have been...
pushed, Dr. Winkel?

478
00:35:12,989 --> 00:35:17,926
""Vinkel.""
I cannot give an opinion.

479
00:35:17,994 --> 00:35:22,431
The injuries to the head and skull
would have been the same.

480
00:35:29,338 --> 00:35:32,273
Major, may I see you
for a moment, please?

481
00:35:32,341 --> 00:35:34,502
Certainly, Brodsky.
What is it?

482
00:35:34,577 --> 00:35:39,207
This forgery is very clever,
and we are interested in this case.

483
00:35:39,282 --> 00:35:41,273
- Have you arrested the girl?
- No, not yet.

484
00:35:41,350 --> 00:35:45,309
Please, keep this passport to yourself
until I will make some inquiries.

485
00:35:45,388 --> 00:35:48,221
- Will you, Major? Thank you.
- Y es, of course.

486
00:35:48,291 --> 00:35:50,350
Right, sit down,
Miss Schmidt.

487
00:35:50,426 --> 00:35:52,826
We'll send your letters
and things back to you.

488
00:35:52,895 --> 00:35:55,989
- And my passport?
- We'll need that for a while.

489
00:36:01,037 --> 00:36:03,528
What did he mean?

490
00:36:03,606 --> 00:36:06,040
You know as much as I do.

491
00:36:06,108 --> 00:36:11,375
Miss Schmidt, you were intimate
with Lime, weren't you?

492
00:36:11,447 --> 00:36:14,211
We loved each other.
Do you mean that?

493
00:36:14,283 --> 00:36:16,751
- Do you know this man?
- I've never seen him.

494
00:36:16,819 --> 00:36:19,185
- Joseph Harbin.
- No.

495
00:36:19,255 --> 00:36:23,191
- He works in a military hospital.
- No.

496
00:36:23,259 --> 00:36:27,628
It's stupid to lie to me, Miss Schmidt.
I'm in a position to help you.

497
00:36:27,697 --> 00:36:29,858
I'm not lying.

498
00:36:29,932 --> 00:36:32,594
You're wrong about Harry.
You're wrong about everything.

499
00:36:32,668 --> 00:36:37,298
In one of his letters,
he asked you to telephone
a good friend of his called Joseph.

500
00:36:37,373 --> 00:36:40,308
He gave you the number
of the Casanova Club.

501
00:36:40,376 --> 00:36:44,369
That's where a lot of friends
of Lime used to go.

502
00:36:44,447 --> 00:36:48,178
- It wasn't important.
- What was the message?

503
00:36:48,250 --> 00:36:50,912
Something about
meeting Harry at his home.

504
00:36:50,987 --> 00:36:54,423
Harbin disappeared
the day you telephoned.

505
00:36:54,490 --> 00:36:57,618
We've got to find him.
You can help us.

506
00:36:59,462 --> 00:37:02,863
What can I tell you, but you've
got everything upside down.

507
00:37:02,932 --> 00:37:08,199
Okay. That American friend
of yours is still waiting for you.

508
00:37:08,270 --> 00:37:11,762
He won't do you much good.

509
00:37:14,443 --> 00:37:17,378
I thank you, Miss Schmidt.
We'll send for you when we want you.

510
00:37:22,118 --> 00:37:25,110
[ Man Speaking German ]

511
00:37:25,187 --> 00:37:28,623
Hello, Mr. Martins. I've been
trying to get you at your hotel.

512
00:37:28,691 --> 00:37:30,955
I've arranged that lecture
for tomorrow.

513
00:37:31,027 --> 00:37:34,087
- Well, what about?
- On the modern novel.
You remember what we arranged.

514
00:37:34,163 --> 00:37:37,132
- Oh.
- They want you to talk
on the Crisis of Faith.

515
00:37:37,199 --> 00:37:40,293
- What's that?
- Oh, I thought you'd know.
You're a writer.

516
00:37:40,369 --> 00:37:43,304
But of course you do. Good night,
old man. I've forgotten my hat.

517
00:37:43,372 --> 00:37:45,806
- I'll let you know the time later.
- Mmm.

518
00:37:45,875 --> 00:37:48,776
[ Violin ]

519
00:37:53,916 --> 00:37:56,111
- Drink?
- Whiskey.

520
00:37:56,185 --> 00:37:58,244
Two whiskeys.

521
00:38:02,892 --> 00:38:05,053
- Zwei Whisky.
- How much?

522
00:38:05,127 --> 00:38:07,857
- Twenty shillings.
- Oh, they don't take army money here.

523
00:38:07,930 --> 00:38:09,864
How much did he say?

524
00:38:11,801 --> 00:38:14,827
- Harry?
- Yes.

525
00:38:14,904 --> 00:38:17,964
He moved his head,
but the rest is good, isn't it?

526
00:38:33,989 --> 00:38:36,549
- Good evening, Miss Schmidt.
- Good evening.

527
00:38:36,625 --> 00:38:39,059
You've found out
my little secret.

528
00:38:39,128 --> 00:38:42,620
A man must live.
How goes the investigation?

529
00:38:42,698 --> 00:38:44,859
Have you proved
the policemen are wrong?

530
00:38:44,934 --> 00:38:47,402
- Not yet.
- But you will.

531
00:38:47,470 --> 00:38:51,031
Our friend Dr. Winkel said
you had called. Wasn't he helpful?

532
00:38:51,107 --> 00:38:53,098
Well, he was limited.

533
00:38:53,175 --> 00:38:56,110
- But Mr. Popescu is here tonight.
- The Romanian?

534
00:38:56,178 --> 00:38:58,442
- Yes, the man who helped carry him.
- I thought he'd left Vienna.

535
00:38:58,514 --> 00:39:00,607
He's back now.

536
00:39:00,683 --> 00:39:03,914
Well, I'd like to meet
all of Harry's friends.

537
00:39:03,986 --> 00:39:06,113
I'll bring him to you.

538
00:39:06,188 --> 00:39:09,157
Haven't you done
enough for tonight?

539
00:39:09,225 --> 00:39:13,889
The porter said three men carried
the body, and two of them are here.

540
00:39:18,234 --> 00:39:20,634
Who are you
lookin' for now?

541
00:39:20,703 --> 00:39:24,400
Shh. Shh.
Don't. Please don't.

542
00:39:24,473 --> 00:39:26,441
Silly lookin' bunch.

543
00:39:28,644 --> 00:39:31,408
- Mr. Popescu, Mr. Martins.
- How do you do?

544
00:39:31,480 --> 00:39:34,506
- Any friend of Harry
is a friend of mine.
- I'll leave you together.

545
00:39:34,583 --> 00:39:38,280
- Good evening, Miss Schmidt.
You remember me?
- Of course.

546
00:39:38,354 --> 00:39:41,414
- I helped Harry
fix her papers, Mr. Martins.
- Oh, you did?

547
00:39:41,490 --> 00:39:44,254
Not a sort of thing
I should confess to a stranger,

548
00:39:44,326 --> 00:39:46,658
but you have to break
the rules sometimes.

549
00:39:46,729 --> 00:39:50,688
Humanity is a duty. Cigarette,
Miss Schmidt? Keep the pack.

550
00:39:50,766 --> 00:39:53,257
I understand
you were with Harry--

551
00:39:53,335 --> 00:39:56,168
Two double whiskeys.
[ Speaking German ]

552
00:39:59,108 --> 00:40:03,545
It was a terrible thing. I was just
crossing the road to go to Harry.

553
00:40:03,612 --> 00:40:06,877
He and the baron
were on the sidewalk.

554
00:40:06,949 --> 00:40:10,680
Maybe if I hadn't started to cross
the road, it wouldn't have happened.

555
00:40:10,753 --> 00:40:14,849
I can't help blaming myself
and wishing things had been different.

556
00:40:14,924 --> 00:40:20,123
Anyway, he saw me and stepped
off the sidewalk to meet me.

557
00:40:20,196 --> 00:40:22,494
And the truck--

558
00:40:22,565 --> 00:40:26,865
It was terrible, Mr. Martins. Terrible.
I've never seen a man killed before.

559
00:40:26,936 --> 00:40:29,905
I think there was something
funny about the whole thing.

560
00:40:29,972 --> 00:40:32,202
- Funny?
- Something wrong.

561
00:40:32,274 --> 00:40:35,539
Of course there was.
Some ice for Mr. Martins.

562
00:40:35,611 --> 00:40:38,409
- You think so too?
- It was so terribly stupid...

563
00:40:38,480 --> 00:40:41,938
for a man like Harry to be killed
in an ordinary street accident.

564
00:40:42,017 --> 00:40:44,212
- That's all you meant?
- What else?

565
00:40:44,286 --> 00:40:47,050
Who was the third man?

566
00:40:47,122 --> 00:40:49,955
[ Chuckles ]
I oughtn't to drink it.

567
00:40:50,025 --> 00:40:52,152
It makes me acid.

568
00:40:52,228 --> 00:40:54,992
What man would you be
referring to, Mr. Martins?

569
00:40:55,064 --> 00:40:57,999
I was told that a third man
helped you and Kurtz carry the body.

570
00:40:58,067 --> 00:41:01,503
I don't know how you got that idea.
You'll find all about it
in the police report.

571
00:41:01,570 --> 00:41:04,403
There was just the two of us,
me and the baron.

572
00:41:04,473 --> 00:41:06,873
Who could have told you
a story like that?

573
00:41:06,942 --> 00:41:10,036
The porter at Harry's place.
He was cleaning the window at the time.

574
00:41:10,112 --> 00:41:12,046
And saw the accident?

575
00:41:12,114 --> 00:41:16,016
No, he didn't see the accident,
but he saw three men carrying the body.

576
00:41:16,085 --> 00:41:18,849
Why wasn't he
at the police inquiry?

577
00:41:18,921 --> 00:41:20,912
He doesn't want
to get involved.

578
00:41:20,990 --> 00:41:23,857
You'll never teach these
Austrians to be good citizens.

579
00:41:23,926 --> 00:41:26,451
It was his duty
to give the evidence.

580
00:41:26,528 --> 00:41:28,462
Even so, he remembers wrong.

581
00:41:28,530 --> 00:41:30,828
What else did he tell you?

582
00:41:30,899 --> 00:41:34,494
That Harry was dead before
you got him to that statue.

583
00:41:34,570 --> 00:41:37,334
He probably knows
a lot more than that.

584
00:41:37,406 --> 00:41:39,966
- Somebody's lying.
- Hmm, not necessarily.

585
00:41:40,042 --> 00:41:43,068
The police say he was
mixed up in some racket?

586
00:41:43,145 --> 00:41:46,945
Oh, that's quite impossible.
He had a great sense of duty.

587
00:41:47,016 --> 00:41:49,610
Your friend Kurtz seems
to think it was possible.

588
00:41:49,685 --> 00:41:53,951
I understand how an Anglo-Saxon feels.
The baron hasn't traveled, you know?

589
00:41:54,023 --> 00:41:56,753
He seems to have
been around a bit.

590
00:41:56,825 --> 00:41:59,817
Do you know a man
called, uh, Harbin?

591
00:41:59,895 --> 00:42:02,762
- No.
- Joseph Harbin.

592
00:42:02,831 --> 00:42:05,061
Joseph Harbin? No.

593
00:42:07,870 --> 00:42:12,569
That's a nice girl, that,
but she ought to go careful in Vienna.

594
00:42:12,641 --> 00:42:16,475
Everybody ought to go careful
in a city like this.

595
00:42:19,715 --> 00:42:23,014
He will meet us
at the bridge. Good.

596
00:43:00,122 --> 00:43:03,853
Hello! Is it
so very important for you?

597
00:43:03,926 --> 00:43:06,451
- Y es, it is.
- I am not a bad man.

598
00:43:06,528 --> 00:43:08,826
I'd like to tell you something.

599
00:43:08,897 --> 00:43:10,831
Tell me, how did the car--

600
00:43:10,899 --> 00:43:15,029
Shh, shh. Come tonight.
My wife goes out.

601
00:43:15,104 --> 00:43:18,505
- All right, I'll come back, but--
- Shh. Tonight.

602
00:43:32,388 --> 00:43:34,379
- [ Knocking At Door ]
- [ Speaking German ]

603
00:43:34,456 --> 00:43:36,447
Does that mean come in?

604
00:43:36,525 --> 00:43:38,493
Oh, yes, come in.

605
00:43:38,560 --> 00:43:40,653
The porter's going
to talk to us tonight.

606
00:43:40,729 --> 00:43:42,822
Need we go through it
all again?

607
00:43:42,898 --> 00:43:45,298
I can manage by myself.
You busy?

608
00:43:45,367 --> 00:43:47,835
Just another part
I've got to learn.

609
00:43:47,903 --> 00:43:50,064
Can I hear you?

610
00:43:50,139 --> 00:43:52,198
- In German?
- I can try.

611
00:43:52,274 --> 00:43:55,903
- Is it comedy or tragedy?
- Comedy. I don't play tragedy.

612
00:43:55,978 --> 00:43:58,412
- Do l, uh, read--
- Well, you read this.

613
00:43:58,480 --> 00:44:01,506
Oh. Well, l--

614
00:44:01,583 --> 00:44:04,643
[ Speaking Broken German ]

615
00:44:04,720 --> 00:44:08,087
- What's that?
- Uh, Heurigen, I guess.

616
00:44:08,157 --> 00:44:10,421
H- E-Z-T--

617
00:44:10,492 --> 00:44:13,017
Oh, let me see.
No, no, that's not the cue.

618
00:44:13,095 --> 00:44:16,030
It means
she has to sit down.

619
00:44:18,801 --> 00:44:23,170
Well, uh, Frau Hausman--

620
00:44:24,339 --> 00:44:27,968
No, no.
It's no good.

621
00:44:30,679 --> 00:44:32,613
Bad day?

622
00:44:32,681 --> 00:44:35,616
It's always bad around this time.

623
00:44:35,684 --> 00:44:38,619
He used to look in around 6.:0.

624
00:44:40,422 --> 00:44:44,483
I've been frightened. I've been alone
without friends and money.

625
00:44:44,560 --> 00:44:47,859
But I've never known
anything like this.

626
00:44:49,565 --> 00:44:52,966
Please talk.
Tell me about him.

627
00:44:53,035 --> 00:44:54,969
Tell you what?

628
00:44:55,037 --> 00:44:59,633
Oh, anything. Just talk. Where did you
see him last, and what did you do?

629
00:44:59,708 --> 00:45:02,768
Oh, we didn't make much sense.
We drank too much.

630
00:45:02,845 --> 00:45:05,780
- Once he tried to steal my girl.
- Where is she?

631
00:45:08,016 --> 00:45:11,247
- Oh, that was nine years ago.
- Tell me more.

632
00:45:11,320 --> 00:45:15,256
[ Clears Throat ]
Well, it's very difficult.
You knew Harry.

633
00:45:15,324 --> 00:45:17,986
We didn't do anything
very amusing.

634
00:45:18,060 --> 00:45:21,029
He just made everything
seem like such fun.

635
00:45:21,096 --> 00:45:24,998
- Was he clever when he was a boy?
- He could fix anything.

636
00:45:25,067 --> 00:45:27,934
- What sort of things?
- Oh, little things.

637
00:45:28,003 --> 00:45:32,167
How to put your temperature up
before exam. The best crib.

638
00:45:32,241 --> 00:45:34,766
How to avoid this and that.

639
00:45:34,843 --> 00:45:37,437
He fixed my papers for me.

640
00:45:37,513 --> 00:45:42,280
He heard the Russians
were repatriating people like me
who came from Czechoslovakia.

641
00:45:42,351 --> 00:45:45,479
He knew the right person
straightaway for forging stamps.

642
00:45:45,554 --> 00:45:47,112
Yeah.

643
00:45:47,189 --> 00:45:50,249
When he was 14, he taught me
the three-card trick.

644
00:45:50,325 --> 00:45:54,421
- That's growing up fast.
- He never grew up.

645
00:45:54,496 --> 00:45:57,624
The world grew up
around him, that's all.

646
00:45:59,268 --> 00:46:01,793
And buried him.

647
00:46:01,870 --> 00:46:05,135
Anna, you'll
fall in love again.

648
00:46:05,207 --> 00:46:08,040
Don't you see
I don't want to?

649
00:46:08,110 --> 00:46:10,044
I don't ever want to.

650
00:46:10,112 --> 00:46:12,672
Come on out and have a drink.

651
00:46:12,748 --> 00:46:15,239
Why did you say that?

652
00:46:15,317 --> 00:46:17,785
Seemed like a good idea.

653
00:46:17,853 --> 00:46:20,583
It was just what he used to say.

654
00:46:20,656 --> 00:46:24,649
Well, uh, I didn't
learn that from him.

655
00:46:24,726 --> 00:46:27,320
If we have to see the porter,
we'd better go.

656
00:46:27,396 --> 00:46:30,490
What's the hurry? Can't we talk
quietly for a couple of minutes?

657
00:46:30,566 --> 00:46:33,831
- I thought you wanted--
- A moment ago, you said you
didn't want to see the porter.

658
00:46:33,902 --> 00:46:37,429
- We're both in it, Harry.
- Holly.

659
00:46:37,506 --> 00:46:39,770
I'm so sorry.

660
00:46:39,841 --> 00:46:43,675
It's all right.
You might get my name right.

661
00:46:46,682 --> 00:46:50,516
You know, you ought
to find yourself a girl.

662
00:46:50,586 --> 00:46:53,612
His English is so very bad,
we'll let him talk German.

663
00:46:53,689 --> 00:46:57,216
- If you'll be good enough to trans--
- Look.

664
00:46:57,292 --> 00:47:01,023
- That's Harry's place, isn't it?
- Y es.

665
00:47:01,096 --> 00:47:04,031
- Let's go away.
- What's the matter?

666
00:47:04,099 --> 00:47:08,365
- Let's not get into any more trouble.
- Wait here.

667
00:47:12,774 --> 00:47:15,834
What's the matter?
Uh, what is, los?

668
00:47:15,911 --> 00:47:19,210
- [ Speaking German ]
- l-I don't understand.

669
00:47:19,281 --> 00:47:22,114
Um, porter, uh, dead.

670
00:47:22,184 --> 00:47:24,118
Kaputt.

671
00:47:24,186 --> 00:47:27,451
The porter is odraht. Kaputt.

672
00:47:27,522 --> 00:47:29,456
- Porter?
- He's murdered.

673
00:47:29,524 --> 00:47:31,458
Papa!

674
00:47:32,894 --> 00:47:37,263
[ Both Speaking German ]

675
00:47:41,169 --> 00:47:43,467
Ja, Papa!

676
00:47:43,538 --> 00:47:46,735
[ Boy Continues Shouting In German ]

677
00:47:49,845 --> 00:47:52,211
[ Speaking German ]

678
00:47:54,449 --> 00:47:56,849
I, uh, don't understand.

679
00:47:56,918 --> 00:48:00,081
[ Continues Shouting In German ]

680
00:48:06,928 --> 00:48:10,329
- What is it?
- The porter's been murdered.

681
00:48:10,399 --> 00:48:14,358
[ Chattering In German ]

682
00:48:16,271 --> 00:48:18,705
They think you did it.

683
00:48:18,774 --> 00:48:21,004
[ Boy Continues Shouting In German ]

684
00:48:33,855 --> 00:48:37,621
[ Speaking German ]
Hello?

685
00:48:45,033 --> 00:48:47,831
- Papa!
- [ Man Shouts In German ]

686
00:49:10,425 --> 00:49:12,359
[ lndistinct ]

687
00:49:12,427 --> 00:49:14,418
[ Man Shouts In German ]

688
00:49:21,603 --> 00:49:25,039
[ Movie Soundtrack In German ]

689
00:49:26,908 --> 00:49:30,503
Sneak out the other way
and go back to your theater.
I'd better not see you again.

690
00:49:30,579 --> 00:49:33,139
- What are you going to do?
- I wish I knew.

691
00:49:33,215 --> 00:49:35,513
Be sensible.
Tell Major Calloway.

692
00:49:35,584 --> 00:49:38,314
[ Movie Soundtrack Continues ]

693
00:49:39,921 --> 00:49:42,947
[ Speaking German ]

694
00:49:50,632 --> 00:49:53,226
[ Horn Honking ]

695
00:49:56,772 --> 00:49:59,536
- Get me Major Callaghan on the phone.
- Oh, Mr. Martins.

696
00:49:59,608 --> 00:50:03,408
- It's very urgent.
Just get him on the telephone.
- Do you know his number?

697
00:50:03,478 --> 00:50:06,914
- No, I don't know his number.
- I'll look it up for you.

698
00:50:06,982 --> 00:50:09,951
- Is there a car here?
- Of course.
There's one waiting for you.

699
00:50:10,018 --> 00:50:13,249
- [ Speaking German ]
- Never mind about the number.

700
00:50:20,962 --> 00:50:23,260
Take me to the headquarters--

701
00:50:26,835 --> 00:50:30,168
Hold on! I haven't even
told you where to take me yet!

702
00:50:30,238 --> 00:50:33,230
- [ Speaking German ]
- [ Tires Screeching ]

703
00:50:33,308 --> 00:50:37,438
- Driver! Driver!
- [ Tires Screeching ]

704
00:50:37,512 --> 00:50:41,471
- Slow down!
- [ Horn Honking ]

705
00:50:41,550 --> 00:50:44,451
Have you got orders to kill me?

706
00:51:01,570 --> 00:51:06,303
[ Horn Honks, Tires Screeching ]

707
00:51:06,374 --> 00:51:09,275
[ Tires Skidding ]

708
00:51:11,513 --> 00:51:14,107
[ Speaking German ]

709
00:51:16,751 --> 00:51:20,778
Ah, ah, ah! Ah, Mr. Martins!
What a relief to see you.

710
00:51:20,856 --> 00:51:23,654
I was beginning to think
something had happened to you.

711
00:51:23,725 --> 00:51:27,320
Everything's ready for you.
I was frantic in case you hadn't got...

712
00:51:27,395 --> 00:51:29,795
my message at the hotel.

713
00:51:29,865 --> 00:51:32,595
Porters out here
are so unreliable.

714
00:51:32,667 --> 00:51:34,635
We're all set
for a wonderful meeting.

715
00:51:34,703 --> 00:51:37,001
You'll find the audience
most appreciative.

716
00:51:37,072 --> 00:51:39,472
Oh, let me take your coat.
I've got it.

717
00:51:39,541 --> 00:51:42,738
There'll be refreshments afterwards.
Come along. Follow me.

718
00:51:42,811 --> 00:51:45,302
Well, here we are,
ladies and gentlemen.

719
00:51:45,380 --> 00:51:47,541
Would you look after those?
Thank you.

720
00:51:47,616 --> 00:51:50,483
Would you like to sit there?
That's right.

721
00:51:50,552 --> 00:51:54,579
I have much pleasure in introducing
Mr. Holly Martins from the other side.

722
00:51:54,656 --> 00:51:56,920
[ Applause ]

723
00:51:59,628 --> 00:52:02,529
Well--
[ Clears Throat ]

724
00:52:02,597 --> 00:52:05,930
Bring the car and anyone
else who would like to come.

725
00:52:06,001 --> 00:52:09,027
Don't be long. Hmm.

726
00:52:12,641 --> 00:52:16,168
Y eah, well, l-- I suppose
that is what I meant to say.

727
00:52:16,244 --> 00:52:18,178
Of course, of course.

728
00:52:18,246 --> 00:52:23,013
Do you believe, Mr. Martins,
in the stream of consciousness?

729
00:52:23,084 --> 00:52:27,350
Stream of consciousness?
Well, uh-- Well, uh--

730
00:52:27,422 --> 00:52:31,051
- Well, uh--
- What author
has chiefly influenced you?

731
00:52:31,126 --> 00:52:33,993
- Grey.
- Grey? What Grey?

732
00:52:34,062 --> 00:52:37,554
- Zane Grey.
- That's Mr. Martins'
little joke, of course.

733
00:52:37,632 --> 00:52:40,931
We know perfectly well Zane Grey
wrote what we call westerns.

734
00:52:41,002 --> 00:52:42,993
Cowboys and bandits.

735
00:52:43,071 --> 00:52:47,132
[ Man ] Mr. James Joyce--
Now, where would you put him?

736
00:52:48,944 --> 00:52:51,469
Oh, uh, would you mind
repeating that question?

737
00:52:51,546 --> 00:52:54,743
I said, where would you put
Mr. James Joyce?

738
00:52:54,816 --> 00:52:57,580
In what category?

739
00:52:57,652 --> 00:53:01,315
Can I ask, is Mr. Martins
engaged on a new book?

740
00:53:01,389 --> 00:53:05,257
Y es. It's called The Third Man.

741
00:53:05,327 --> 00:53:08,421
- A novel, Mr. Martins?
- It's a murder story.

742
00:53:08,496 --> 00:53:11,795
I've just started it.
It's based on fact.

743
00:53:11,866 --> 00:53:15,893
Why, it's Mr. Popescu!
Oh, very great pleasure to see you here.

744
00:53:15,971 --> 00:53:20,601
As you know, Mr. Popescu
is a very great supporter
of one of our medical charities.

745
00:53:20,675 --> 00:53:23,644
Are you a slow writer,
Mr. Martins?

746
00:53:23,712 --> 00:53:26,272
Not when I get interested.

747
00:53:26,348 --> 00:53:29,340
I'd say you were doing something
pretty dangerous this time.

748
00:53:29,417 --> 00:53:32,648
- Y eah?
- Mixing fact and fiction.

749
00:53:32,721 --> 00:53:36,350
- Should I make it all fact?
- Why, no, Mr. Martins.

750
00:53:36,424 --> 00:53:38,858
I'd say stick to fiction.
Straight fiction.

751
00:53:38,927 --> 00:53:41,828
I'm too far along
with the book, Mr. Popescu.

752
00:53:41,896 --> 00:53:44,990
- Haven't you ever
scrapped a book, Mr. Martins?
- Never.

753
00:53:45,066 --> 00:53:46,829
Pity.

754
00:53:46,901 --> 00:53:48,835
[ Chattering In German ]

755
00:53:48,903 --> 00:53:51,428
Ladies and gentlemen,
if there are no more questions,

756
00:53:51,506 --> 00:53:54,031
I think I can call the meeting
officially closed.

757
00:54:12,260 --> 00:54:13,784
That's him.

758
00:54:30,145 --> 00:54:34,013
[ Clattering, Moaning ]

759
00:54:34,082 --> 00:54:37,347
Who's there?
Who is it? Who is it?

760
00:54:37,419 --> 00:54:39,717
[ Moaning Continues ]

761
00:54:39,788 --> 00:54:42,655
It's all right.
It's all right.

762
00:54:43,925 --> 00:54:46,655
[ Squawking ]

763
00:54:49,497 --> 00:54:53,433
- [ Squawking Continues ]
- [ Footsteps Approaching ]

764
00:55:14,456 --> 00:55:17,687
[ Train Whistle Blows ]

765
00:55:46,121 --> 00:55:48,487
I told you
to go away, Martins.

766
00:55:48,556 --> 00:55:52,117
This isn't Santa Fe, I'm not a sheriff
and you aren't a cowboy.

767
00:55:52,193 --> 00:55:55,162
You've been blundering around with
the worst bunch of racketeers in Vienna,

768
00:55:55,230 --> 00:55:57,824
Harry's friends,
and now you're wanted for murder.

769
00:55:57,899 --> 00:56:00,390
- Put down drunk and disorderly too.
- I have.

770
00:56:00,468 --> 00:56:03,528
- What's the matter with your hand?
- Parrot bit me.

771
00:56:03,605 --> 00:56:05,869
Oh, stop behaving
like a fool, Martins.

772
00:56:05,940 --> 00:56:09,376
I'm only a little fool. I'm an amateur
at it. You're a professional.

773
00:56:09,444 --> 00:56:12,208
You've been shaking your
cap and bells all over town.

774
00:56:12,280 --> 00:56:15,215
Get me the Harry Lime file,
and get Mr. Martins a whiskey.

775
00:56:15,283 --> 00:56:17,751
I don't need
your drinks, Calloway.

776
00:56:17,819 --> 00:56:21,050
You will. I don't want
another murder in this case,

777
00:56:21,122 --> 00:56:23,352
so you're going to hear
the facts.

778
00:56:23,424 --> 00:56:26,325
You haven't told me
a single one yet.

779
00:56:26,394 --> 00:56:28,988
Have you ever heard
of penicillin?

780
00:56:29,063 --> 00:56:30,860
Well?

781
00:56:30,932 --> 00:56:33,696
In Vienna, there hasn't been
enough penicillin to go around.

782
00:56:33,768 --> 00:56:35,929
So a nice trade started here..

783
00:56:36,004 --> 00:56:39,098
Stealing penicillin
from the military hospitals,

784
00:56:39,174 --> 00:56:42,940
diluting it to make it go further,
and selling it to patients.

785
00:56:43,011 --> 00:56:44,945
Do you see what that means?

786
00:56:45,013 --> 00:56:48,176
Are you too busy chasing a few tubes
of penicillin to investigate a murder?

787
00:56:48,249 --> 00:56:50,581
These were murders.

788
00:56:50,652 --> 00:56:52,813
Men with gangrened legs,

789
00:56:52,887 --> 00:56:55,549
women in childbirth,
and there were children too.

790
00:56:55,623 --> 00:56:59,184
They used some of this diluted
penicillin against meningitis.

791
00:56:59,260 --> 00:57:01,194
The lucky children died.

792
00:57:01,262 --> 00:57:04,698
The unlucky ones went off their heads.
You can see them now in the mental ward.

793
00:57:04,766 --> 00:57:07,633
That was the racket
Harry Lime organized.

794
00:57:07,702 --> 00:57:10,899
Calloway, you haven't shown me
one shred of evidence.

795
00:57:10,972 --> 00:57:16,171
We're just coming to that.
Paine, magic lantern show.

796
00:57:16,244 --> 00:57:18,178
Very good, sir.

797
00:57:18,246 --> 00:57:20,373
[ Calloway ]
Paine's one of your devoted readers.

798
00:57:20,448 --> 00:57:22,916
He's promised to lend me one
of your books. Which one is it, Paine?

799
00:57:22,984 --> 00:57:25,077
The Lone Rider of Santa Fe, sir.

800
00:57:25,153 --> 00:57:29,055
- That's right.
- I'd like to visit Texas one day, sir.

801
00:57:29,123 --> 00:57:32,286
- Come on, show me
what you've got to show.
- All right, Paine?

802
00:57:32,360 --> 00:57:33,987
Y es, sir.

803
00:57:36,331 --> 00:57:38,390
Paine, Paine, Paine.

804
00:57:38,466 --> 00:57:42,562
I got them muddled. It's the new lot
that's just come in for Mr. Crabbin.

805
00:57:44,472 --> 00:57:47,635
See this man here?
A fellow called Harbin,

806
00:57:47,709 --> 00:57:50,576
a medical orderly
at the General Hospital.

807
00:57:50,645 --> 00:57:54,445
He worked for Lime and helped to steal
the stuff from the laboratories.

808
00:57:54,515 --> 00:57:59,179
We forced him to give information to us
which led us as far as Kurtz and Lime.

809
00:57:59,254 --> 00:58:04,055
But we didn't arrest them,
as it might have spoiled our
chances of getting the others.

810
00:58:04,125 --> 00:58:07,424
- Next, Paine.
- I'd like a word
with this orderly, Harbin.

811
00:58:07,495 --> 00:58:09,759
- So would l.
- Well, bring him in.

812
00:58:09,831 --> 00:58:12,391
I can't.
He disappeared a week ago.

813
00:58:12,467 --> 00:58:15,197
This is more like a mortuary
than police headquarters.

814
00:58:15,270 --> 00:58:18,034
We have better witnesses.
Look here.

815
00:58:45,800 --> 00:58:48,268
How could he have done it?

816
00:58:48,336 --> 00:58:50,327
Seventy pounds a tube.

817
00:58:50,405 --> 00:58:53,636
Go back to the hotel,
and do keep out of trouble.

818
00:58:53,708 --> 00:58:57,303
I'll try and fix things
with the Austrian police.
You'll be all right in the hotel,

819
00:58:57,378 --> 00:58:59,573
but I can't be responsible
for you on the streets.

820
00:58:59,647 --> 00:59:02,912
- I'm not asking you to.
- I'm sorry, Martins.

821
00:59:02,984 --> 00:59:04,952
I'm sorry too.

822
00:59:07,655 --> 00:59:09,919
You still got that
airplane ticket on you?

823
00:59:09,991 --> 00:59:12,585
We'll send one across
to your hotel in the morning.

824
00:59:12,660 --> 00:59:14,855
Thank you.
Excuse me.

825
00:59:14,929 --> 00:59:17,591
Get me Austrian Police Headquarters.

826
00:59:17,665 --> 00:59:19,758
Can I have that woman's passport?

827
00:59:19,834 --> 00:59:22,530
You know,
the Anna Schmidt one.

828
00:59:22,603 --> 00:59:25,868
Oh... we're not going to pick
her up for that, are we?

829
00:59:25,940 --> 00:59:29,637
What can we do?
We have our instructions.

830
00:59:36,484 --> 00:59:39,248
[ Jazz ]

831
01:00:12,687 --> 01:00:15,451
- [ Knocking At Door ]
- [ Speaking German ]

832
01:00:15,523 --> 01:00:18,083
[ Holly ]
It's me.

833
01:00:21,829 --> 01:00:23,763
It's me.

834
01:00:28,803 --> 01:00:30,737
Hello.

835
01:00:30,805 --> 01:00:32,864
What is it?
What's happened to you?

836
01:00:32,940 --> 01:00:36,501
Just came to see you.

837
01:00:36,577 --> 01:00:40,673
Come in. I thought you were going to
keep away. Are the police after you?

838
01:00:40,748 --> 01:00:42,682
I don't know.

839
01:00:44,118 --> 01:00:48,054
- You're drunk, aren't you?
- A bit. I'm sorry.

840
01:00:50,091 --> 01:00:54,027
But I did want to say good-bye
before I pushed off.

841
01:00:54,095 --> 01:00:56,359
- I'm going back home.
- Why?

842
01:00:58,032 --> 01:01:01,593
It's what you've always wanted--
all of you.

843
01:01:02,670 --> 01:01:04,934
Kitty? Here, kitty.

844
01:01:05,006 --> 01:01:07,804
Kitty? Here, kitty.
Kitty, kitty, kitty, kitty.

845
01:01:07,875 --> 01:01:11,367
Don't you want to play, kitty?
Come on. Sleepy? Sleepy kitty?

846
01:01:13,514 --> 01:01:16,972
- Not very sociable, is he?
- No, he only liked Harry.

847
01:01:18,519 --> 01:01:21,454
- What made you decide so suddenly?
- l, I brought you these.

848
01:01:21,522 --> 01:01:23,752
They, they got a little wet.

849
01:01:23,825 --> 01:01:27,784
- What happened to your hand?
- A parrot--

850
01:01:27,862 --> 01:01:31,628
- Let it go.
- Have you seen Calloway?

851
01:01:31,699 --> 01:01:34,930
- lmagine a parrot nipping a man?
- Have you?

852
01:01:35,002 --> 01:01:39,336
It's--
Oh, l, l--

853
01:01:39,407 --> 01:01:42,672
I've been saying good-bye
all over, you know.

854
01:01:42,743 --> 01:01:47,271
- He told you, didn't he?
- Told me?

855
01:01:47,348 --> 01:01:51,182
- About Harry.
- Do you know?

856
01:01:53,221 --> 01:01:55,587
I've seen Major Calloway today.

857
01:02:23,718 --> 01:02:25,652
[ Meows ]

858
01:02:37,298 --> 01:02:40,665
He is better dead.

859
01:02:40,735 --> 01:02:43,704
I knew he was mixed-up,
but not like that.

860
01:02:43,771 --> 01:02:47,730
I knew him for 20 years--
at least, I thought I knew him.

861
01:02:47,808 --> 01:02:51,300
Suppose he was laughing
at fools like us all the time?

862
01:02:51,379 --> 01:02:55,076
- He liked to laugh.
- Seventy pounds a tube.

863
01:02:55,149 --> 01:02:59,313
He wanted me to write
for his great medical charity.

864
01:02:59,387 --> 01:03:01,582
I'll put these flowers
in the water.

865
01:03:01,656 --> 01:03:05,387
Perhaps I could have raised
the price to 80 pounds for him.

866
01:03:05,459 --> 01:03:09,088
Oh, please. For heaven's sake,
stop making him in your image.

867
01:03:09,163 --> 01:03:12,826
Harry was real. He wasn't
just your friend and my lover.

868
01:03:12,900 --> 01:03:16,734
- He was Harry.
- Well, don't preach wisdom to me.

869
01:03:16,804 --> 01:03:22,333
You talk about him as if
he had occasional bad manners.

870
01:03:22,410 --> 01:03:26,938
No. I don't know. I'm just
a hack writer who drinks too much...

871
01:03:27,014 --> 01:03:30,108
and falls in love with girls.

872
01:03:31,953 --> 01:03:35,514
- You.
- Me?

873
01:03:35,590 --> 01:03:37,717
Don't be such a fool.
Of course.

874
01:03:39,327 --> 01:03:42,694
If you'd rung me up and asked me
were you fair or dark...

875
01:03:42,763 --> 01:03:45,857
or had a moustache,
I wouldn't have known.

876
01:03:45,933 --> 01:03:47,867
Oh, I am leaving Vienna.

877
01:03:47,935 --> 01:03:51,598
I don't care whether Henry
was murdered by Kurtz or Popescu...

878
01:03:51,672 --> 01:03:54,106
or the third man or--

879
01:03:54,175 --> 01:03:59,579
Whoever killed him, there was
some sort of... justice.

880
01:03:59,647 --> 01:04:01,945
Maybe I would've
killed him myself.

881
01:04:02,016 --> 01:04:04,450
A person doesn't change
because you find out more.

882
01:04:04,518 --> 01:04:09,888
Look. I've got a splitting
headache, and you stand there
and just talk and talk and talk.

883
01:04:09,957 --> 01:04:12,619
I- I hate it.

884
01:04:12,693 --> 01:04:16,720
That's the first time
I ever saw you laugh.

885
01:04:16,797 --> 01:04:18,731
Do it again.

886
01:04:23,170 --> 01:04:25,604
There isn't enough for two laughs.

887
01:04:35,116 --> 01:04:39,052
I'd make comic faces...

888
01:04:39,120 --> 01:04:42,783
and stand on my head and grin
at you between my legs...

889
01:04:44,358 --> 01:04:47,555
and tell all sorts of jokes.

890
01:04:49,997 --> 01:04:52,431
I wouldn't stand a chance,
would l?

891
01:05:03,544 --> 01:05:05,478
Well...

892
01:05:07,415 --> 01:05:11,647
you did tell me I ought
to find myself a girl.

893
01:05:30,571 --> 01:05:33,005
[ Cat Meowing ]

894
01:05:41,148 --> 01:05:44,982
[ Man ] What kind of a spy
do you think you are, satchel foot?

895
01:05:46,921 --> 01:05:49,481
What are you tailing me for?

896
01:05:51,792 --> 01:05:53,726
Cat got your tongue?

897
01:05:55,763 --> 01:05:58,197
Come on out.

898
01:05:58,265 --> 01:06:01,564
Come out, come out,
whoever you are.

899
01:06:03,704 --> 01:06:06,502
Step out in the light
and let's have a look at ya.

900
01:06:06,574 --> 01:06:09,771
- Who's your boss?
- [ Woman Speaking German ]

901
01:06:23,124 --> 01:06:25,718
Harry.

902
01:06:27,595 --> 01:06:29,893
[ Speaking German ]

903
01:06:35,469 --> 01:06:37,767
[ Car Horn Honks ]

904
01:06:42,109 --> 01:06:44,771
[ Footsteps Running Away ]

905
01:06:51,819 --> 01:06:53,548
[ Holly ]
Harry!

906
01:07:40,768 --> 01:07:42,929
I followed his shadow...

907
01:07:43,003 --> 01:07:44,937
until, suddenly--

908
01:07:45,005 --> 01:07:47,997
- Well?
- This is where he vanished.

909
01:07:48,075 --> 01:07:51,306
- I see.
- I suppose you don't believe me.

910
01:07:51,378 --> 01:07:53,710
- No.
- Look. I tell you--

911
01:07:53,781 --> 01:07:56,011
- You don't think I'm blind, do you?
- Yes.

912
01:07:56,083 --> 01:07:58,984
- Where were you when you saw him first?
- Fifty yards right down there.

913
01:07:59,053 --> 01:08:02,022
- Which side of the road?
- I was on that side.
His shadow was on that side.

914
01:08:02,089 --> 01:08:04,717
- And there are no turnings
on either side.
- What about the doorways?

915
01:08:04,792 --> 01:08:07,056
- I tell you, I heard him
running ahead of me!
- Y es, yes, yes.

916
01:08:07,127 --> 01:08:10,688
And then he vanished out there,
I suppose, with a puff of smoke
and like a clap of--

917
01:08:28,883 --> 01:08:31,317
It wasn't the German gin.

918
01:08:32,820 --> 01:08:35,755
[ Low Roaring ]

919
01:08:59,546 --> 01:09:02,515
Well, what's this?
Where are we?

920
01:09:02,583 --> 01:09:05,518
It's the main sewer.

921
01:09:05,586 --> 01:09:09,420
Runs right into the blue Danube.
Smells sweet, doesn't it?

922
01:09:12,760 --> 01:09:16,025
We should have dug deeper
than a grave.

923
01:09:29,009 --> 01:09:30,943
[ Creaking ]

924
01:09:32,813 --> 01:09:35,976
[ Creaking Continues ]

925
01:09:36,050 --> 01:09:38,610
[ Speaking German ]

926
01:09:39,987 --> 01:09:42,114
[ German ]

927
01:09:46,794 --> 01:09:49,228
[ Creaking Continues ]

928
01:10:03,744 --> 01:10:05,678
You knew him, Major?

929
01:10:05,746 --> 01:10:09,238
Hmm. Yes.

930
01:10:09,316 --> 01:10:11,341
Yes. Joseph Harbin.

931
01:10:11,418 --> 01:10:13,978
Medical orderly
at the General Hospital.

932
01:10:16,156 --> 01:10:18,989
- He used to work for Harry Lime.
- Joseph Harbin?

933
01:10:19,059 --> 01:10:23,826
Yes. He's the man
I told you was missing.

934
01:10:25,299 --> 01:10:27,790
Next time we'll have
a foolproof coffin.

935
01:10:36,810 --> 01:10:39,040
[ Speaking Russian ]

936
01:10:48,389 --> 01:10:51,324
[ Speaking German ]

937
01:10:59,233 --> 01:11:01,667
[ Footsteps Approaching ]

938
01:11:05,339 --> 01:11:07,273
[ Knock At Door ]

939
01:11:07,341 --> 01:11:09,775
- [ Man Speaking German ]
- [ Speaking German ]

940
01:11:09,843 --> 01:11:11,777
[ German Continues ]

941
01:11:30,998 --> 01:11:33,694
- Fraulein Schmidt?
- Ja.

942
01:11:33,767 --> 01:11:35,894
[ Speaking German ]

943
01:12:02,362 --> 01:12:05,297
[ Woman Speaking German ]

944
01:12:08,669 --> 01:12:11,604
[ Continues Complaining In German ]

945
01:12:37,431 --> 01:12:41,492
- Where are you taking me?
- lnternational Police Headquarters,
just to check up.

946
01:12:41,568 --> 01:12:43,433
[ German ]

947
01:12:49,510 --> 01:12:52,946
I'm sorry, miss. It's orders.
We can't go against the protocol.

948
01:12:53,013 --> 01:12:55,982
- I don't even know what protocol means.
- Neither do l, miss.

949
01:12:56,049 --> 01:12:59,143
Mademoiselle,
your lipstick.

950
01:12:59,219 --> 01:13:01,153
Thank you.

951
01:13:13,800 --> 01:13:16,394
- Anna, what's happened to you?
- All right. Keep out of this.

952
01:13:16,470 --> 01:13:19,268
Listen, I've got to talk to you.
I've just seen a dead man walking.

953
01:13:19,339 --> 01:13:22,934
- All right, chum. Get back.
- I saw him buried.

954
01:13:23,010 --> 01:13:25,808
But now I've seen him alive.

955
01:13:32,452 --> 01:13:34,920
Just a minute.
Bring her in here.

956
01:13:39,560 --> 01:13:41,790
You stay out here.

957
01:13:41,862 --> 01:13:46,128
Come in, Miss Schmidt.
Now then, Miss Schmidt.

958
01:13:46,200 --> 01:13:49,636
I'm not interested in your forged
papers. That's purely a Russian case.

959
01:13:49,703 --> 01:13:53,139
- When did you last see Lime?
- Two weeks ago.

960
01:13:53,207 --> 01:13:56,506
I want the truth, Miss Schmidt.
We know he's alive.

961
01:13:56,577 --> 01:14:00,809
- It is true, then.
- Joseph Harbin's body
was found in the coffin.

962
01:14:02,316 --> 01:14:04,250
What did you say?
I'm sorry.

963
01:14:04,318 --> 01:14:07,810
I said another man
was buried in his place.

964
01:14:07,888 --> 01:14:09,822
Where's Harry?

965
01:14:09,890 --> 01:14:12,518
That's what we want
to find out.

966
01:14:14,094 --> 01:14:17,860
I'm sorry. I don't seem able
to understand anything you say. I--

967
01:14:18,932 --> 01:14:20,866
He is alive.

968
01:14:20,934 --> 01:14:23,027
Now this minute,
he is doing something.

969
01:14:23,103 --> 01:14:27,130
Miss Schmidt, we know he's somewhere
across the canal in the Russian sector.

970
01:14:27,207 --> 01:14:29,471
You may as well help us.
In a few minutes,

971
01:14:29,543 --> 01:14:32,011
Colonel Brodsky will be questioning you
about your papers.

972
01:14:32,079 --> 01:14:35,640
- Tell me where Lime is.
- I don't know.

973
01:14:35,716 --> 01:14:39,083
If you help me,
I am prepared to help you.

974
01:14:39,152 --> 01:14:42,644
Martins always said
you were a fool.

975
01:14:42,723 --> 01:14:46,284
Vienna is a closed city, Miss Schmidt.
He can't get away. Right.

976
01:14:46,360 --> 01:14:48,294
Poor Harry.

977
01:14:49,529 --> 01:14:51,861
I wish he was dead.

978
01:14:52,966 --> 01:14:55,434
He would be safe
from all of you, then.

979
01:15:05,078 --> 01:15:08,411
Why, that's you!
Come up.

980
01:15:08,482 --> 01:15:11,315
Winkel, look who is here.

981
01:15:11,385 --> 01:15:13,319
I want to speak to you, Kurtz.

982
01:15:13,387 --> 01:15:15,912
- Of course. Come up.
- I'll wait here.

983
01:15:15,989 --> 01:15:19,447
- I don't understand.
- I want to talk to Harry.

984
01:15:20,627 --> 01:15:22,754
- Are you mad?
- All right. I'm mad.

985
01:15:22,829 --> 01:15:26,458
I've seen a ghost.
You tell Harry I want to see him.

986
01:15:27,901 --> 01:15:30,165
Be reasonable.
Come up and talk.

987
01:15:30,237 --> 01:15:33,866
No, thank you.
I like the open.

988
01:15:33,940 --> 01:15:37,842
Tell him I'll wait
by that wheel there.

989
01:15:37,911 --> 01:15:40,846
Or do ghosts only rise
by night, Dr. Winkel?

990
01:15:42,449 --> 01:15:45,247
You got an opinion on that?

991
01:16:47,214 --> 01:16:51,275
- Hello, old man. How are you?
- Hello, Harry.

992
01:16:51,351 --> 01:16:54,013
Well, well, they seem to be
giving you quite some busy time.

993
01:16:54,087 --> 01:16:56,419
- Well, listen. I want to talk to you.
- Hmm, yes?

994
01:16:56,490 --> 01:17:00,051
Talk to me?
Well, of course. Come on.

995
01:17:02,896 --> 01:17:05,228
Kids used to ride this thing
a lot in the old days.

996
01:17:05,298 --> 01:17:09,530
- But they haven't
the money now, poor devils.
- [ Speaking German ]

997
01:17:09,603 --> 01:17:12,538
Listen, Harry.
I didn't believe that--

998
01:17:12,606 --> 01:17:15,234
- It's good to see you, Holly.
- I was at your funeral.

999
01:17:15,308 --> 01:17:17,776
That was pretty smart,
wasn't it?

1000
01:17:17,844 --> 01:17:20,005
Oh, the same old indigestion, Holly.

1001
01:17:20,080 --> 01:17:22,241
These are the only things
that help, these tablets.

1002
01:17:22,315 --> 01:17:25,045
These are the last. Can't get 'em
anywhere in Europe anymore.

1003
01:17:25,118 --> 01:17:27,552
- Do you know what's happened
to your girl?
- Hmm?

1004
01:17:27,621 --> 01:17:30,351
- She's been arrested.
- Tough, very tough,
but don't worry, old man.

1005
01:17:30,424 --> 01:17:33,086
- They won't hurt her.
- They're handing her over
to the Russians.

1006
01:17:33,160 --> 01:17:35,390
What can I do, old man?
I'm dead, aren't l?

1007
01:17:35,462 --> 01:17:37,396
- You can help some.
- Holly,

1008
01:17:37,464 --> 01:17:40,228
exactly who did you tell
about me, hmm?

1009
01:17:40,300 --> 01:17:43,269
- I told the police.
- Unwise, Holly.

1010
01:17:43,336 --> 01:17:45,531
- And Anna.
- Unwise.

1011
01:17:45,605 --> 01:17:48,335
Did the, uh,
police believe you?

1012
01:17:48,408 --> 01:17:50,376
You don't care anything at all
about Anna, do you?

1013
01:17:50,444 --> 01:17:52,378
[ Chuckling ]
I've got quite a lot on my mind.

1014
01:17:52,446 --> 01:17:54,914
- You wouldn't do anything.
- What do you want me to do?
Be reasonable.

1015
01:17:54,981 --> 01:17:57,677
- You can get somebody else--
- Do you expect me to give myself up?

1016
01:17:57,751 --> 01:18:00,185
- Why not?
- It's a far better thing that I do...

1017
01:18:00,253 --> 01:18:02,187
with the old limelight
than follow the curtain--

1018
01:18:02,255 --> 01:18:05,554
No. You and I aren't heroes.
The world doesn't make any heroes--

1019
01:18:05,625 --> 01:18:08,059
- You've got plenty of contacts.
- Outside of your stories.

1020
01:18:08,128 --> 01:18:10,096
I've got to be so careful.

1021
01:18:10,163 --> 01:18:13,564
I'm only safe in the Russian zone. I'm
only safe as long as they can use me.

1022
01:18:13,633 --> 01:18:16,761
- As long as they can use you?
- I wish I could get rid of this thing.

1023
01:18:16,837 --> 01:18:20,329
So that's how they found out about Anna.
You told them, didn't you?

1024
01:18:20,407 --> 01:18:22,375
Don't try to be a policeman,
old man.

1025
01:18:22,442 --> 01:18:24,876
- What do you expect me to be?
Part of your--
- Part?

1026
01:18:24,945 --> 01:18:28,711
You can have any part
as long as you don't interfere.
I've never cut you out of anything.

1027
01:18:28,782 --> 01:18:32,445
Yes, I remember when they raided the
gambling joint, you knew a safe way out.

1028
01:18:32,519 --> 01:18:35,454
- Sure!
- Yeah, safe for you. Not safe for me.

1029
01:18:35,522 --> 01:18:40,186
Old man, you never should have
gone to the police, you know.

1030
01:18:40,260 --> 01:18:43,229
You ought to leave
this thing alone.

1031
01:18:43,296 --> 01:18:46,129
Have you ever seen
any of your victims?

1032
01:18:46,199 --> 01:18:49,600
You know, I never feel comfortable
on these sort of things.

1033
01:18:49,669 --> 01:18:52,194
Victims?
Don't be melodramatic.

1034
01:18:54,074 --> 01:18:56,201
Tell me.

1035
01:18:56,276 --> 01:19:01,111
Would you really feel any pity if one
of those dots stopped moving forever?

1036
01:19:01,181 --> 01:19:04,378
If I offered you L20,000
for every dot that stopped,

1037
01:19:04,451 --> 01:19:06,885
would you really, old man,
tell me to keep my money?

1038
01:19:06,953 --> 01:19:10,980
Or would you calculate how many
dots you could afford to spend?

1039
01:19:11,057 --> 01:19:13,992
Free of income tax, old man.
Free of income tax--

1040
01:19:14,060 --> 01:19:16,790
the only way
you can save money nowadays.

1041
01:19:16,863 --> 01:19:20,321
- A lot of good your money
will do you in jail.
- That jail's in another zone.

1042
01:19:21,535 --> 01:19:24,333
There's no proof against me,

1043
01:19:24,404 --> 01:19:26,338
besides you.

1044
01:19:33,647 --> 01:19:35,808
I should be pretty easy
to get rid of.

1045
01:19:38,184 --> 01:19:41,085
- Pretty easy.
- I wouldn't be too sure.

1046
01:19:41,154 --> 01:19:44,021
I carry a gun.

1047
01:19:44,090 --> 01:19:47,548
I don't think they'd look for a bullet
wound after you hit that ground.

1048
01:19:50,330 --> 01:19:52,423
They dug up your coffin.

1049
01:19:56,236 --> 01:19:58,170
And found Harbin?

1050
01:20:02,776 --> 01:20:04,710
Mm-hmm.

1051
01:20:06,846 --> 01:20:08,905
Pity.
[ Chuckles ]

1052
01:20:08,982 --> 01:20:12,509
Holly, what fools we are
talking to each other this way,

1053
01:20:12,586 --> 01:20:15,350
as though I'd do anything to you
or you to me.

1054
01:20:15,422 --> 01:20:18,220
You're just a little mixed-up
about things in general.

1055
01:20:18,291 --> 01:20:22,057
Nobody thinks in terms
of human beings.

1056
01:20:22,128 --> 01:20:24,062
Governments don't.
Why should we?

1057
01:20:24,130 --> 01:20:27,793
They talk about the people
and the proletariat. I talk
about the suckers and the mugs.

1058
01:20:27,867 --> 01:20:33,737
It's the same thing. They have their
five-year plans, and so have l.

1059
01:20:33,807 --> 01:20:36,503
You used to believe in God.

1060
01:20:36,576 --> 01:20:39,340
I still do believe in God,
old man.

1061
01:20:40,447 --> 01:20:44,178
I believe in God and mercy
and all that.

1062
01:20:44,250 --> 01:20:46,616
But the dead are happier dead.

1063
01:20:46,686 --> 01:20:49,780
They don't miss much here,
poor devils.

1064
01:20:53,493 --> 01:20:55,427
What do you believe in?

1065
01:20:55,495 --> 01:20:58,931
Oh, if we ever get Anna out
of this mess, be kind to her.

1066
01:20:58,999 --> 01:21:00,990
I think you'll find
she's worth it.

1067
01:21:01,067 --> 01:21:04,161
I wish I'd asked you to bring me
some of these tablets from home.

1068
01:21:04,237 --> 01:21:08,003
Holly, I'd like to cut you in,
old man.

1069
01:21:08,074 --> 01:21:12,135
There's nobody left in Vienna
I can really trust, and we've
always done everything together.

1070
01:21:12,212 --> 01:21:15,613
When you make up your mind,
send me a message.
I'll meet you anyplace, anytime.

1071
01:21:15,682 --> 01:21:18,651
And when we do meet, old man,
it's you I want to see,

1072
01:21:18,718 --> 01:21:20,879
not the police.

1073
01:21:20,954 --> 01:21:22,888
Remember that, won't you?

1074
01:21:22,956 --> 01:21:26,517
[ Chuckling ] And don't be so gloomy!
After all, it's not that awful.

1075
01:21:26,593 --> 01:21:29,061
Remember what the fella said:

1076
01:21:29,129 --> 01:21:33,793
In ltaly, for 30 years under
the Borgias, they had warfare,
terror, murder, bloodshed.

1077
01:21:33,867 --> 01:21:37,496
But they produced Michelangelo,
Leonardo da Vinci and the Renaissance.

1078
01:21:37,570 --> 01:21:39,970
In Switzerland,
they had brotherly love.

1079
01:21:40,040 --> 01:21:44,568
They had 500 years of democracy
and peace, and what did that produce?

1080
01:21:44,644 --> 01:21:47,442
The cuckoo clock.
So long, Holly.

1081
01:21:55,689 --> 01:21:58,453
But look here, Martins.
You can always arrange to meet him at,

1082
01:21:58,525 --> 01:22:01,255
at some little cafe here
in the international zone.

1083
01:22:01,327 --> 01:22:03,261
- It would never work.
- We'll never get him
in the Russian zone.

1084
01:22:03,329 --> 01:22:06,127
Calloway, you expect too much.

1085
01:22:06,199 --> 01:22:09,168
Oh, I know he deserves to hang.
You've proved your stuff,

1086
01:22:09,235 --> 01:22:12,693
but 20 years is a long time.

1087
01:22:12,772 --> 01:22:15,400
Don't ask me to tie the rope.

1088
01:22:15,475 --> 01:22:17,739
Okay. Forget it.

1089
01:22:17,811 --> 01:22:20,974
- Busy, Major?
- What is it, Brodsky?

1090
01:22:21,047 --> 01:22:24,448
We have identified the girl.
Here is her report.

1091
01:22:26,052 --> 01:22:28,247
[ Calloway ] I've questioned her.
We've got nothing against her.

1092
01:22:28,321 --> 01:22:31,779
We shall apply for her at
the Four Power meeting tomorrow.

1093
01:22:31,858 --> 01:22:34,486
She has no right to be here.

1094
01:22:36,062 --> 01:22:38,929
I've asked your people
to help with Lime.

1095
01:22:38,998 --> 01:22:42,695
That's a different case.
It is being looked into.

1096
01:22:42,769 --> 01:22:45,169
- So long, Major.
- [ Door Closes ]

1097
01:22:45,238 --> 01:22:50,403
[ Calloway ]
In the last war, a general would hang
his opponent's picture on the wall.

1098
01:22:50,477 --> 01:22:52,604
He got to know him that way.

1099
01:22:52,679 --> 01:22:55,580
I'm beginning to know Lime.

1100
01:22:55,648 --> 01:22:59,744
I think this would've worked,
with your help.

1101
01:23:06,159 --> 01:23:08,093
What price would you pay?

1102
01:23:14,701 --> 01:23:17,226
Name it.

1103
01:23:17,303 --> 01:23:21,239
[ Train Whistle Blowing,
Man Speaking German Over Loudspeaker ]

1104
01:23:26,813 --> 01:23:28,747
[ German Continues ]

1105
01:23:45,365 --> 01:23:48,027
Here we are.
You'll be all right here, miss.

1106
01:23:51,638 --> 01:23:54,129
I don't understand
Major Calloway. I--

1107
01:23:54,207 --> 01:23:58,109
- I expect he's got
a soft spot for you, miss.
- Why has he done all this?

1108
01:23:58,178 --> 01:24:02,137
Don't you worry, miss.
You're well out of things.

1109
01:24:02,215 --> 01:24:04,206
There we are, miss.

1110
01:24:04,284 --> 01:24:07,776
- Thank you. You've been so kind.
- Well, I'll be saying good night.

1111
01:24:09,989 --> 01:24:12,514
- Good night, miss.
- Good-bye.

1112
01:24:12,592 --> 01:24:14,992
[ Man Speaking German Over Loudspeaker ]

1113
01:24:33,413 --> 01:24:35,347
[ Train Whistle Blows ]

1114
01:24:49,896 --> 01:24:54,492
- Are you going too?
- Oh.

1115
01:24:54,567 --> 01:24:57,866
- What are you doing here?
- I wanted to see you off.

1116
01:24:57,937 --> 01:24:59,700
See me off?
From here?

1117
01:24:59,772 --> 01:25:04,471
Oh, I watched you onto the train, uh--
No harm in that, is there?

1118
01:25:04,544 --> 01:25:06,978
How did you know
I'd be here?

1119
01:25:07,046 --> 01:25:10,812
I heard something about it
at police headquarters.

1120
01:25:10,884 --> 01:25:13,375
Have you been seeing
Major Calloway again?

1121
01:25:13,453 --> 01:25:16,251
Of course not.
I don't live in his pocket.

1122
01:25:17,624 --> 01:25:19,558
Harry, what is it?

1123
01:25:21,027 --> 01:25:24,019
- For heaven sakes,
stop calling me Harry.
- I'm sorry.

1124
01:25:24,097 --> 01:25:26,190
- [ Man On Loudspeaker, lndistinct ]
- Let's go.

1125
01:25:26,266 --> 01:25:28,291
What's on your mind?
Why did you hide here?

1126
01:25:28,368 --> 01:25:31,997
Hide? Can't a fellow have a drink?
Here. It'll be cold on that train.

1127
01:25:32,071 --> 01:25:34,631
- I shall be all right.
- You send me a wire as soon as you are.

1128
01:25:34,707 --> 01:25:37,505
- What's going to happen?
Where is Harry?
- He's safe in the Russian zone.

1129
01:25:37,577 --> 01:25:39,875
- How do you know?
- Well, I saw him today.

1130
01:25:39,946 --> 01:25:42,380
- How is he?
- He can look after himself.
Don't worry.

1131
01:25:42,448 --> 01:25:45,349
- Did he say anything about me?
Tell me!
- Oh, the usual things.

1132
01:25:45,418 --> 01:25:48,478
- Is something wrong?
Did you tell Calloway about Harry?
- Of course I didn't.

1133
01:25:48,554 --> 01:25:51,284
Why should he help me?
The Russians will make trouble for him.

1134
01:25:51,357 --> 01:25:54,224
- That's his headache. Oh, Anna!
- His? Why are you lying?

1135
01:25:54,294 --> 01:25:56,956
- We're getting you
out of here, aren't we?
- I'm not going.

1136
01:25:57,030 --> 01:25:59,225
You'd--

1137
01:25:59,299 --> 01:26:02,791
Anna, don't you recognize
a good turn when you see one?

1138
01:26:02,869 --> 01:26:05,429
You have seen Calloway?
What are you two doing?

1139
01:26:07,473 --> 01:26:11,432
Well, they, they asked me
to help take him.

1140
01:26:11,511 --> 01:26:13,445
I'm helping.

1141
01:26:22,588 --> 01:26:25,819
- Poor Harry.
- Poor Harry.

1142
01:26:27,794 --> 01:26:32,094
Poor Harry... wouldn't even
lift a finger to help you.

1143
01:26:32,165 --> 01:26:36,101
Oh, you've got your precious honesty
and don't want anything else.

1144
01:26:36,169 --> 01:26:38,137
You still want him.

1145
01:26:38,204 --> 01:26:40,365
I don't want him anymore.

1146
01:26:40,440 --> 01:26:45,400
I don't want to see him, hear him, but
he's still a part of me. That's a fact.

1147
01:26:45,478 --> 01:26:47,810
I couldn't do a thing
to harm him.

1148
01:26:47,880 --> 01:26:50,110
[ Train Whistle Blowing ]

1149
01:26:50,183 --> 01:26:53,084
[ Train Departing ]

1150
01:27:06,666 --> 01:27:12,002
Oh, Anna, why do we always
have to quarrel?

1151
01:27:12,071 --> 01:27:16,440
If you want to sell your services,
I'm not willing to be the price.

1152
01:27:19,145 --> 01:27:22,308
I loved him.
You loved him.

1153
01:27:22,382 --> 01:27:25,579
What good have we done him...
for love?

1154
01:27:27,453 --> 01:27:29,444
Look at yourself.

1155
01:27:29,522 --> 01:27:32,855
They have a name
for faces like that.

1156
01:27:54,480 --> 01:27:56,539
- Calloway.
- Come in here. There isn't much time.

1157
01:27:56,616 --> 01:27:59,881
I want to get a plane
out of here tonight.

1158
01:27:59,952 --> 01:28:02,716
- So she talked you out of it.
- Gave me these.

1159
01:28:04,157 --> 01:28:06,148
A girl of spirit.

1160
01:28:06,225 --> 01:28:10,286
She's right.
It is none of my business.

1161
01:28:10,363 --> 01:28:14,561
It won't make any difference
in the long run. I'll get him.

1162
01:28:14,634 --> 01:28:19,071
- Well, I won't have helped.
- That'll be a fine boast to make.

1163
01:28:19,138 --> 01:28:22,266
- Well, I always wanted you
to catch that plane, didn't l?
- You all did.

1164
01:28:22,341 --> 01:28:27,074
I'd better see if there's
anyone still at the terminus.
You may need a priority.

1165
01:28:28,948 --> 01:28:31,246
Mind if I drop off
somewhere on the way?

1166
01:28:31,317 --> 01:28:34,218
- I've got an appointment.
It won't take five minutes.
- Of course.

1167
01:28:34,287 --> 01:28:37,381
Why don't you come in too?
You're a writer. It might interest you.

1168
01:28:38,658 --> 01:28:41,593
This is the biggest children's
hospital in Vienna.

1169
01:28:41,661 --> 01:28:44,858
All the kids in here are the result
of Lime's penicillin racket.

1170
01:29:05,485 --> 01:29:09,819
He'd had meningitis.
They gave it some of Lime's penicillin.

1171
01:29:10,857 --> 01:29:12,791
Terrible pity, isn't it?

1172
01:29:39,819 --> 01:29:43,846
Paine lent me one of your books.
Oklahoma Kid, I think it was.

1173
01:29:43,923 --> 01:29:46,517
I read a bit of it. Looks as if
it's gonna be pretty good.

1174
01:29:46,592 --> 01:29:51,029
What made you take up this sort
of thing? Been doing it for long?

1175
01:29:51,097 --> 01:29:54,362
- All right, Calloway. You win.
- I never knew there were
snake charmers in Texas.

1176
01:29:54,433 --> 01:29:57,425
- I said you win.
- Win what?

1177
01:29:57,503 --> 01:30:02,099
I'll be your...
dumb decoy duck.

1178
01:30:55,494 --> 01:30:57,428
Psst!

1179
01:31:06,939 --> 01:31:08,873
Paine.

1180
01:31:34,700 --> 01:31:36,634
Look, sir!

1181
01:31:43,376 --> 01:31:45,310
How much longer
are you going to sit here?

1182
01:31:45,378 --> 01:31:47,403
Shall I go over there, sir?

1183
01:31:47,480 --> 01:31:50,415
No. No,
leave them for a while.

1184
01:32:10,002 --> 01:32:12,562
[ Old Man ]
Mein Herr, Ballon?

1185
01:32:12,638 --> 01:32:15,129
Nein, danke. Nein.

1186
01:32:17,977 --> 01:32:20,241
- Ballon?
- [ Speaking German ]

1187
01:32:20,313 --> 01:32:24,340
[ German Continues ]
Go on. Hop it, scarper.

1188
01:32:24,417 --> 01:32:28,183
- Ballon, mein Herr?
- [ German Continues ]

1189
01:32:33,759 --> 01:32:37,593
All right, all right.
Only one. Go on, scarper.

1190
01:33:15,201 --> 01:33:19,035
You should have gone.
How did you know I was here, anyway?

1191
01:33:19,105 --> 01:33:22,597
From Kurtz.
They have just been arrested.

1192
01:33:22,675 --> 01:33:25,576
But Harry won't come.
He's not a fool.

1193
01:33:25,644 --> 01:33:29,842
- Yes, Paine. Slip over there.
See what she's up to.
- Right, sir.

1194
01:33:29,915 --> 01:33:33,214
[ Anna ]
Don't tell me you are doing
all this for nothing.

1195
01:33:34,987 --> 01:33:37,421
- What's your price this time?
- No price, Anna.

1196
01:33:37,490 --> 01:33:40,288
Honest, sensible, sober,

1197
01:33:40,359 --> 01:33:42,691
harmless Holly Martins.

1198
01:33:42,762 --> 01:33:45,925
Holly.
What a silly name.

1199
01:33:45,998 --> 01:33:50,697
You must feel very proud
to be a police informer.

1200
01:33:52,638 --> 01:33:56,005
Harry, get away!
The police are outside!

1201
01:33:56,075 --> 01:33:57,440
- Quick!
- Anna.

1202
01:33:59,512 --> 01:34:01,377
[ Door Opens ]

1203
01:34:02,848 --> 01:34:05,248
Sir, the back!

1204
01:34:05,317 --> 01:34:07,251
[ Whistles Blowing ]

1205
01:34:09,488 --> 01:34:12,889
- [ Whistle Blowing Continues ]
- [ Dogs Barking ]

1206
01:34:15,761 --> 01:34:18,855
[ Siren Wailing ]

1207
01:34:24,970 --> 01:34:26,904
[ Wailing Continues ]

1208
01:35:06,212 --> 01:35:08,146
All right.

1209
01:35:09,215 --> 01:35:11,979
[ Gunshots ]

1210
01:35:17,556 --> 01:35:19,490
[ Calloway ]
Martins, get back!

1211
01:35:31,670 --> 01:35:35,037
[ Speaking German ]

1212
01:35:43,349 --> 01:35:45,840
[ German Continues ]

1213
01:35:48,888 --> 01:35:51,015
[ German ]

1214
01:35:58,397 --> 01:36:00,661
[ Man Shouts ]

1215
01:36:08,240 --> 01:36:12,472
[ Shouting In German ]

1216
01:36:16,448 --> 01:36:18,382
[ Sirens Wailing ]

1217
01:36:22,922 --> 01:36:25,356
[ Dogs Barking ]

1218
01:36:26,725 --> 01:36:31,185
[ German Continues ]

1219
01:36:35,267 --> 01:36:38,327
[ German Continues ]

1220
01:37:01,694 --> 01:37:04,128
[ German Continues ]

1221
01:37:26,218 --> 01:37:28,709
[ Footsteps Echoing ]

1222
01:37:34,126 --> 01:37:38,085
- [ Footsteps Continue ]
- [ German ]

1223
01:37:38,163 --> 01:37:40,859
- [ German Continues ]
- [ Whistles Blowing ]

1224
01:37:53,679 --> 01:37:55,840
[ Speaking German ]

1225
01:38:00,352 --> 01:38:02,786
[ Footsteps Approaching ]

1226
01:38:20,439 --> 01:38:23,101
[ German Continues ]

1227
01:38:54,139 --> 01:38:56,334
- [ Barking ]
- [ Shouts In German ]

1228
01:39:03,882 --> 01:39:06,817
[ German Continues ]

1229
01:39:32,678 --> 01:39:36,671
Harry!

1230
01:39:36,749 --> 01:39:38,580
- Is that you?
- You're through.

1231
01:39:38,650 --> 01:39:40,743
Come out. You haven't
got a chance this way.

1232
01:39:40,819 --> 01:39:43,913
- What do you want?
- You might as well give up.

1233
01:39:43,989 --> 01:39:46,958
Mr. Martins, sir,
get back, get back!

1234
01:39:47,025 --> 01:39:50,188
Keep back, sir!
Come back! Come back, sir!

1235
01:40:16,188 --> 01:40:18,952
[ Grunts ]

1236
01:41:25,724 --> 01:41:27,851
Martins! Martins!

1237
01:41:27,926 --> 01:41:30,690
Be careful, Martins.

1238
01:41:30,762 --> 01:41:35,062
Don't take any chances.
If you see him, shoot!

1239
01:41:54,052 --> 01:41:55,986
[ Gunshot ]

1240
01:42:09,234 --> 01:42:12,169
[ Speaking German ]

1241
01:42:35,627 --> 01:42:37,618
What time is it?

1242
01:42:37,696 --> 01:42:40,187
- [ Engine Starts ]
- 2:30.

1243
01:42:43,835 --> 01:42:47,100
I'll have to step on it
if you're going to catch that plane.

1244
01:42:47,172 --> 01:42:51,268
Calloway, can't you
do something about Anna?

1245
01:42:51,343 --> 01:42:54,801
I'll do what I can,
if she'll let me.

1246
01:43:05,057 --> 01:43:08,925
- Wait a minute. Let me out.
- Well, there's not much time.

1247
01:43:08,994 --> 01:43:12,930
One can't just leave.
Please.

1248
01:43:14,032 --> 01:43:16,398
Be sensible, Martins.

1249
01:43:16,468 --> 01:43:19,096
I haven't got a sensible name,
Calloway.

